Beaumont-cum-Moze, Harwick, Essex}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af1 \ltrch\fcs0 \f1\insrsid6311765\charrsid16072257 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-490\li518\ri0\sa240\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin518\itap0\pararsid6311765 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Whereabouts was it in Thorpe that you used to live when you were born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Abbey Street.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Where is that in relation to the High Street in Thorpe?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
It runs - it's a continuation of it, towards - Kirby and - and Frinton and Walton. You go - by the Memorial, straight on to Frinton, and that's Abbey Street. Well the Abbey is on the corner. And - and that's how it gets its name Abbey Street you see.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Was it a cottage?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Oh no, it's rather big house. And - kind of deco}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13902668\charrsid11678041 
rated work in the brickwork abov}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 e - not on the roof but sticking out in front of the roof sort of thing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 You were born in 1889?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 1899, October the 12th.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 The address where you were born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Just Abbey Street, Thorpe-le-Soken. Yes, no name of house, no number or nothing I don't think.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Could you tell me the year you were married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 As near as I can tell you 1921.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Have you been married just once?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 That's all. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 You lived in that house you were born in until you moved to Beaumont?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Yes, about seven years.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Where did you live when you got to Beaumont?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 We lived in an old row houses known as Blue Row. But actually it wasn't blue at all, it was a creamy colour.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Do you know why it was called that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 I don't know. No. Might be by reason of being painted blue. There were six houses in the row.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 They were terraced were they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Well what you call all joining, that is terraced isn't it. I ought to know, I've been a bricklayer. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 How long did you live in Blue Row?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Well - from 19 - about 1907 - I can't quite - afore I married, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 So you were living in that house during the war?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 You think you moved from there sometime between the end of the war and when you got married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Yes. Yes - yes, I must have been - married about 1921 and - we lived in that house two or three years. Yes. No, I don't know exact.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Can you tell me where your father came from?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 My father came from Little Clacton. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 And you said he was a farm worker?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 He's a farm labourer, general farm labourer.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did he ever have any other job?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
Yes, he went to sea as a youth. He was on a fishing smack, my father - wasn't educated at all, he couldn't write. If he wrote - tried to write his name and address he'd be like - be like trying to draw anything you know. But he could 
read, he could read the Bible and the Bible only, and he always read it out aloud. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 How long was he on the fishing smack, do you know?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Not exactly - I should think when he was about fifteen to - eighteen. And he'd draw a smack in two or thre
e minutes. Yes. And say this is the mainsail, this is the job or whatever the sails was, this is the main}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13902668\charrsid11678041  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 sale, this is the }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13902668\charrsid11678041 bi}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 g}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13902668\charrsid11678041  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 sail or all that sort of thing. He'd soon draw a smack in two or three minutes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did he draw to entertain you children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
Yes, just to show us what a smack was like. Yes. He weren't no fool although he weren't educated, he weren't no fool. He'd say to me, you're dull of understanding, if he told me anything you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Could he add up sums and money and that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Well
 the way they used to do it would be - farm workers had to sometimes to check how many bags of corn, they'd do it with chalks. Marks up and down - so many and a line across the top of them somehow, to make it that easier to add 'em up. How many sacks of c
orn come off a - a stack or a stack when they thrashed it. 'Cos then in those days the - to do thrashing it required three things, you got the engine, the drum and the pitcher. Thrashing - yes, thrashing machine and they could do the lot, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 He used to do the thrashing did he?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
He used to help yes. I suppose he could - he could stack the stack. Or he could do - he could - of course when - when the thrasher got to stack the straw haven't they as it came off the pitcher, he could - he could - he co
uld - stack a stack of stalk corn, you know, when they come in off the fields. They weren't like the present day combine. And - and he used to - mow - what they call with a scythe. And - is it all going down in there? And - he used to mow corn with a scyt
h
e with the other men, and they used to tie it with the straws of the corn which my father called bends, but actually - I didn't know at the time, they weren't bends, they were bonds, bonds meaning tie. Means tie. But my father called 'em bends, I - I used
 to - make the bends, I've been in the field making the bends myself for him. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 You used to help him did you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Just a little, because I used to go to see him, you know, not all day long. No - no paid jobs or anything, oh no, just amuse myself.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 When he finished fishing did he carry on farm work all his life after that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Well except the times he was ill.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 He suffered a lot from illness did he?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 He suffered with - with - gastritis I suppose. And there weren't the treatment there 
is today I don't think. And he wasn't educated in any way to do - to do any dieting like I might be. He - he wouldn't understand - to leave some things alone and only eat other things.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Could your mother read and write or not?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 My mother - yes, and she could spell a lot better than any one of us. Yes. But she hadn't done any grammar. Well very little.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Where did she come from?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 I think she was born Thrope-le-Soken. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Do you know if she ever had a job, a paid job?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Not - well, when was married, yes, her used to go pea picking. I don't think my mother did, but some women used to go stone}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13902668\charrsid11678041  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 picking, but I think that'd be more me grandmother's time, used to go stone}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid13902668\charrsid11678041  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 picking, picking up stones in the fields.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 That was hard work wasn't it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Well - monotonous I think, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Your mother was never in service or anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Yes. Yes. She was in service before ever I can remember mind you, yes. Yes. When she's single.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Anything else besides being in service before she married do you know?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
That's the only job that - there wasn't much else. There'd be no factory. There weren't no factory, although there was a - Bramble Isle, that's supposed to be in Beaumont.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 What factory was that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Explosive factory, it's 
there now but - explosive - explosive. But - I understand that they don't employ - only about a quarter of the people - a lot girls, women and girls you know and men, they don't employ about a quarter of what they did. And they're going in for poultry, ke
eping poultry. Yes. And - and - amongst perhaps other things.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Can you tell if you could work out how old your mother was when you were born? You say your father was about forty-six?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Yes, forty-six when he died. He died in 1915. And - and when he 
died he didn't - they didn't take him to - to church or to - to burial - in - in a hearse, he went on a farm wagon. Well the same as what he worked with all his life more - well all his farm working life.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did you go to the funeral?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Can you remember it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Yes. Vividly. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did people wear black?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Well we - yes, I had a black suit. Oh I do definite remember that, I had a black suit.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did you go on wearing black afterwards?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Yes, some while. To worn the suit out you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 What about your mother, or did she wear black in any case?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Well, she was - but she had some - some black, I don't quite remember. She more see that I had something.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Who else went to the funeral, was it just the family or did friends and people go too?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
Oh yes, I think there was some friends going and there's several of us in family. There was thirteen of us. And - I think mother lost - we'd lost our youngest - sister before mother died, I'm sure of that. As a matter of fact
 - is that all going down? As a mater of fact - she went to an isolation hospital and - and she - she'd no - no business to go into isolation hospital, because she got - I think it - menin}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13902668\charrsid11678041 g}
{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 itis, head trouble, and weren't - and weren't - wasn't the - infect
ious disease. So nobody couldn't go and see her, actually only through glass. This was my youngest sister, she was born a bit delicate.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did she die then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 She - she died, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 At your father's funeral did they go back afterwards and have a tea or anything in those days, or have a meal afterwards?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Well we just went home, I don't think there was a - anything special. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 He had another name?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Yes. His - his name was - surname was Baker. He was the eldest. And there was Maude. I 
should think there might have been about three years difference in between because there was one born dead named Alexander and I think he was born in between there you see. Daisy perhaps about - fifteen or sixteen - eighteen months in between. Harry about
 
the same. Albert about the same. Lottie about the same. Nell about the same. Fred about the same. Difference between William, there's; fifteen months in between me and Ted and - about the same, jack about the same, Norah about the same, but I think - I th
ink that make that thirteen, two, three, four, five six, seven, eight, nine, ten, eleven, twelve, thirteen, yes, that's right. Yes. I've not written Alexander properly. Alexandra.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 So there's Arthur, Alexander, Maud, Daisy, Harry, Albert, Lottie, Nellie, Fred, William, Ted, Jack and Norah?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 That was a lot wasn't it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Arthur was born before your parents married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Yes. That's what that amount to, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 When you were living in Abbey Street can you remember how many rooms there were in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
I think there was only - two bedrooms. And two - two downstairs, and one of them was only an old - back place. You know. It wasn't - wasn't - wasn't what you could live in. You could store anything in it. Actually my fath
er worked on a farm and harvest time he had three barrels of home brewed beer. Yes, and we - I liked that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did you have it when you were children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 When did you have it, at mealtimes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Oh no, we'd be in between mealtimes I should think.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Why did you move to Beaumont?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
Well I don't know if - we'd had any complaint, there was more - more - an extra bedroom you see. One thing. You see, earlier on, I - I'd had }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13902668\charrsid11678041 diphtheria}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 , whilst in Abbey Street, and - my brother, younger brothe
r Jack caught it off me and had it bad, I never had it bad, I only had it mildly but - I'd had it bad enough, he caught it off me. And - people used to bring round jellies and all nice sort of things, Jack going down and Fred going down, that's me, you kn
ow. He couldn't eat any, he was ever so badly. He got over it. Nobody else never caught it in the Parish. And they closed all Thorpe-le-Soken for a fortnight because I'd been to school - the doctor reckoned I'd been to school a fortnight with }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13902668\charrsid11678041 diphtheria}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 . I know I got a bad throat and kept going. But - mother didn't know I'd got }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid13902668\charrsid11678041 diphtheria}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
, but the doctor said I'd had it for a fortnight. Nobody else caught it in the Parish, and nobody in the home. And of course - when we was recovering or near enough recovere
d - I remember mother being - pretty bad, whether I was I don't quite remember. Mind you was inoculated in time weren't you. Yes. After the horse had got out sort of thing.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Who brought the jellies round?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 I think a Mrs Abness. Anyway I think she would be one of them, I don't remember nobody else.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Where did she live then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
She lived - same Abbey Street on the other side of the road about - forty yards away. And - and her husband was a blacksmith, horse - a horse shoeing smith and - used 
to put on the - iron tyres on - on - on all the cart - cart - cartwheels, you know, what horses used to pull, there weren't hardly any carts. And of course there was a frame outside, on - nearly on the pavement, what they used to fit these iron tyres to t
o finish them off. And he employed one man named Mr Budney and he lived next door to me, this Mr Budney.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did anyone else help by bringing round food when you were ill?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 I don't remember so, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 It was after that that you moved to Beaumont?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 In Beaumont how many rooms did you have?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
We had three bedrooms. One downstairs which you could live in, the other one - just a lean-to, perhaps showing all the - pan tiles I think they was termed. You look up there you see the tiles sor
t of thing you call 'em, and then there weren't no ceiling to it, just the one living room what was - then a little - able to live in sort of thing. The other weren't fit to live in.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 So where did your mother cook and wash?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Oh in the little kitchen living room, that's all - all in one. Yes, no sink. No sink. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 She didn't have a wash house or anything like that?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 No. We used to have to use the bath - and do it on the kitchen table I suppose, or perhaps that - that - that could be done 
in - the little back place. You could do that in there I suppose, I don't quite remember - I suppose that's where she would do it because, I mean, that was all right for that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 But your father didn't change his job when you moved?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 No, after - he left the water he - he never done nothing else, only farm work.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 He always worked for the same farmer did he?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Oh no, he - when we moved to Beaumont - he worked for a different farmer. Some of the time, not - not right away he didn't. He used to w
ork at - when I was a little boy he worked at a - at a farm called the Follies, best of my memory, up the Frinton Road or Kirkby Road we used to call it, today they call it the Frinton Road. Be a bit posher. He worked at the - at a farm called the Follies
 for a - for Mr Thomson who was a bachelor. And he lived in a - just opposite Thorpe Abbey in a house called - Ivy House, it's there today - with an Ivy leaf on it, with the name on an ivy leaf.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 What was he like as an employer?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 I think he was - he always used to walk along the road humming. Not singing, humming. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Why did he hum do you think?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Oh - kept himself happy I should think.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did anybody else ever live with the family, like any relations or a lodger?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Well you wouldn'
t hardly credit it, yes, sometimes me - me brother Arthur would come home - I don't know where - where we slept 'em, I think there was only two bedrooms, but Arthur and his wife and she was a - a - a Norwich - woman you know. And I used to love to hear he
r talk. Sounded different to us, yes, I think they are, even today I think Norfolk people talk.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Only occasionally people came to stay?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 That's all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 There were no people living with you permanently?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 No, never. No, it was all - it was almost impossible. Yes. You - you couldn't take in a lodger.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did anyone ever help your mother with any housework or anything, did she ever pay anybody to scrub or anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 No, never, no. No. Mater of fact she - sometimes used to do - a bit of was
hing for somebody else and my mother never had very good sight after - about 1906, I could tell you something about that, perhaps I hadn't better. But - she couldn't see too well. Shall I tell you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 How did she lose her sight?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Well - I don't hard
ly know, she used to do a lot of reading, but I'll tell you one thing - if you'll forgive me for telling you. When I was a little boy and we stil}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13902668\charrsid11678041 l - in - when we was in Thorpe-l}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 e-Soken, Charlie Budney who lived next door set mother in an armchair, and she said to me, Fred, your mother is blind. But she wasn't. And it make you think -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Why did he do that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
I don't know. Just to torment me I suppose, oh he was a very nice fellow. Yes. But whether that - soon after that - she suffered with her eyes. She used to read ever such a lot you know. More than ever I do.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 You don't know why her eyes were bad?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
No, don't know. She had cataracts, that's what-s causing it, something called cataracts, and something at the back of the eye an' all. She went to Guys hospital. And one of my - younger brother Ted - she'd been there some while, Ted ain}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13902668\charrsid11678041 \rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
t worried much about mother, went to meet her. 'Cos we lived down that row, Blue - Blue Row was - was no - no longer any there, it was pulled down where we lived at Blue Row. And Ted ain}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13902668\charrsid11678041 
\rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 t worried about mother much you know but when he went to meet my mother, you have been gone a long while, and burst into tears. Ted. Yes. 'Cos he's younger than me.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 You say he didn't worry much about her?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Well you know, some will fret right away, well won't they. Well none of us did as I know of you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did your mother talk to you much and play with you when you were a child?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Oh she never had time to play but she'd talk to me.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 What sort of things would she talk about, tell stories about the old days or anything.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
I suppose she'd read to us sometimes when we couldn't read ourself. Yes, she used to tell us different things, there's different things I know what I - I mean I put in this essay that I shouldn't know unless mother had told me.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Like about when you were born and she had a different midwife?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
Yes. Yes. You see, she was - mother was ill and that affected me, I was born ever so weak and the midwife said, he - washed me, there you are Mr
s Mills, he won't be much trouble to you long, he'll die, sort of thing, that's what she meant. Mother, said, give him back to me, he'll be all right. Which of course I survived didn't I mother - and father though they couldn't hardly afford used to - buy
 me brandy. Then of course - buy me brandy, yes. I can't remember having it mind you, but mother's told me they used to buy me brandy. But one thing I do remember, shall I tell you? Well I can have a slight recollection of King Edward VII Cor}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13902668\charrsid11678041 o}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 nation day. Th
e one thing I can remember is receiving a gold coloured tin - with the Kings head on it, which is King Edward VII, filled - filed with chocolate. But one thing I don't remember - only the result of it, I was scared - frightened badly by somebody in a sack
,
 the men in the sack race. 'Cos I don't remember the sack race. I - I can - at the sports held on - held on Abbey meadow. That Abbey meadow now is full of bungalows and - the - Primitive Methodist church used to hold their Sunday school treat on that litt
le meadow as well. And they used to play football on it. Remember the Ganges a playing Thorpe-le-Soken when I was a little boy, on that Abbey meadow.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Were you a Primitive Methodist?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 No, we were - we were church. Matter of fact I was in Beaumont c
hurch this last Sunday, and that's the first time I've been in that church since 1910. And that's when mother - grandmother was buried. About 1910 when she was bought from Elmstead, she originally lived at Thorpe, Thorpe-le-Soken you see, but I suppose af
t
er her husband - my grandfather died, which was her - her husband, she moved to Elmstead with her - her brother. And died there about 1910 of course, and she was brought from Elmstead in - in what you call a charabier - charabier, and that's a - a hearse 
and a - and the place where the mourners are all in one. You don't see 'em today I don't think. And this was horse}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13902668\charrsid11678041 -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 drawn.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 After you went to that church in 1910 did you never go to any place of worship after?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Oh yes, we went - when we - when we mo
ved from Thorpe to Beaumont, the first Sunday - I goes - makes for Thorpe Sunday school as usual, when we got there we was told we was crossed off the books.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Why was that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 I don't know. They thought you'd gone, you won't come, but I was attendin
g Thorpe - Thorpe day school just the same. Which the school - Sunday school teacher - almost should have known that.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 So what did you do after that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Well we go in to Beaumont chapel Sunday school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Is that Methodist?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Primitive - yes, Wesleyan Methodist you know at that day. Yes. What you pass on that road, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did your mother and father also go to the chapel?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 No don't remember mother going - don't hardly remember going to church much but she used to go to the - the Baptist 
chapel, which it happens is right opposite Thorpe church entrance, and what they used to call p}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13902668\charrsid11678041 rayer meetings. And - and there\rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 s - there's no sermon at the meeting like that, you see what I mean. Just singing and prayers. I think - you - the congregation w
as allowed to pick their own hymns. And I remember going there once or twice like that when I was ever so young.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Was that on Sundays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 No, that - they held them in the midweek in the evening. Prayer meetings, same as they used to at this Baumont 
chapel, used to have the prayer meetings - in the middle of the week, not Sundays.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 What about your father, did he ever go anywhere for worship?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 I don't think he did. Well I don't know, he must have done some of his time 'cos on - I think me sist
ers told me he used to pray in church, well that's a thing I - I've never got to do and couldn't do. But I - I've - I've heard say he used to - pray in church and I suppose that must have been at a prayer meeting 'cos otherwise - unless you're a local pre
acher, you - you don't - you don't say any prayers. As far as ever I know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Can you tell me how your mother managed about clothing all you children, did she sew?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Well - yes, she did and - and my father, I guess I told you was on - was a - on a fis
hing smack, he could make - we used to have to have anything made up. He could make us a pair of trousers out of - out of the - that old pair. Out of an old pair of trousers, small - shorten 'em up you know, smaller. He could do that. But I couldn't. Yes,
 well they learned that when they're at sea you see. That's how I see it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did he do that frequently or not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
Well - when - when - as he see the occasion we want a pair of trousers I suppose. We didn't often have any new - new outer clothes. We had new under}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13902668\charrsid11678041 -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 linen. But don't think little boys in that day wore underpants, 'cos trousers used to be lined. And little boys, even in my time, when they're ever so little they used to wear like girls dresses. Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did your mother make anything or was it your father who did the sewing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
Oh mother used to do some but my father could turn his hand, as I say, I don't think he could alter a - an adult jacket into a - that'd be more difficult wouldn't it, into a small jacket, but he could a pair of trousers. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did they ever get second}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13902668\charrsid11678041  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 hand clothes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Well sometimes we used to go to jumble sales. Yes, buy second}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13902668\charrsid11678041  }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 hand clothes, yes. Or we had some perhaps - 'cos I - I don't ought to tell you this, you - you know be calling what you call cadging, 
going asking other people if they've got any old clothes to give away sort of thing. Yes, used to ask people. Well you see, there were so many of us and never - never - never buy new clothes out of fourteen shillings a week would you, although - as I say,
 there's some have grown up and away before ever I can remember so - there was - never no more than seven of us at home at a time I don't suppose.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 When you were first remembering things had Arthur and Alexander already left home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Yes, but Alexander died, he - he didn't reach the age of one I don't think. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 And had Maud gone away?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Yes, she'd gone away, yes, gone away, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 What did she do?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 She went into service.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 What about Daisy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Well she was always in service.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Was she in service when you were a small child?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
Yes, but I can remember her being at home, just, occasionally, yes, but not Maud, and and not Arthur. Harry I can remember being at home a little while. 'Cos sometimes he worked in Thorpe-le-Soken, h
e worked - he used to - he was in the grocery line a long time and I remember working at the - shop which known as Gaynors at that time of day. Gainses. It was Mitchell}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13902668\charrsid11678041 \rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 s for - more recent year but that's been in different hands a long time now, I forget who - who owns it now.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 What work was he doing in the grocery line?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
Well - well sometimes I've seen him - I remember seeing him out there load - loading up a van, horse drawn van. Serving I suppose in the shop and all. Yes. Yes, in managering the shop.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 You said you went round cadging clothes, did you children go round? Or did your mother come with you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 No, we used to go round ourself, mother never came with us. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 What houses would you go to then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Well where there were boys the likes of me, mind not - not girls.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did you go to the blacksmith's house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
No. No. No, we never - never did go but see sometimes sent - sent anything round. I think she once sent a pair of shoes round. Oh I think they were boots for girl, and 
I think somebody else had them which - she said they was for so and so you know, and - and so and so didn't have 'em and then she come and made a fuss about it. She wanted the one who she said they were for to have them you know. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did she have a special favourite in the family then do you think?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
No, I don't think so. I suppose she thought, that'll just suit that one, you know. I suppose they were girls things I think in that case. Oh no, no, no, no, they must have been boys because - there wa
sn't a girl there 'til - more later in that family. They - they was all boys 'til the last child being a girl. And all those boys - attended school regularly I suppose all their school}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13902668\charrsid11678041 -}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 time they had a big certificate to say that they'd not missed any atten
dance right through the year, and had prize books into the bargain and a big certificate. I've got one somewhere, one of these certificates but - and I had - three for regular attendance prizes I think, and one for good conduct.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 You were a good boy at school then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Yes, pretty good, yes. Good conduct and work I think they term it don't they.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did you ever get new shoes or were they all given to you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Oh no, some was generally - boots not shoes, hardly ever shoes unless they's little old p
limsolls. Kept - often we had a new pair of plimsolls. 'Cos we boys used to run about a lot. They'd run barefooted would some of the boys in Thorpe-le-Soken. Two or three miles.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did you sometimes go there because you didn't have them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 No, no, t
hat wasn't the idea, the others were perhaps - boys were better off than what we were and they same - barefooted. Yes. In - in the warm season of the year mind you.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Where were boots repaired?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 My father did a little but I don't think he was a dab
 hadn't at it, we used to have to - mother used to pay for them to be mended. There's one or two repairers in Thorpe at the time. One man would make them. A Mr Wells. And he used to be postman and all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Were your sisters clothes also made from grown up clothes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
No I don't think so, no. No, I think they must have had 'em a bit different. 'Cos there was what we call a clothing club, I mention 'em in this essays, where you pay perhaps - sixpence or shilling a week. Mother paid it you know. And then w
hen you got enough in could draw it out to get what you wanted. I suppose that time of day you could buy a - a boy's suit for about ten bob.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did somebody come round with the clothing, come to the door?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 No, we didn't - no, you - you go and draw your money out of the clothing club and - and - choose what you want yourself.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 You didn't have to go to a special shop?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 No. No. No, but it wasn't given you see not that, you paid it in yourself you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Do you remember if your father ever helped with any housework, cleaning for example?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 He'd cook, yes, but I don't know so much about cleaning, he'd cook. He - 'cos he's an old coun}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid13902668\charrsid11678041 tryman. He said, a better puddi}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 n}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13902668\charrsid11678041 g}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041  than your mother could make a}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13902668\charrsid11678041 in't it boy? It's a better puddi}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 n}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13902668\charrsid11678041 g}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041  than your own mother can make ain}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13902668\charrsid11678041 \rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 t it by, he'd say to me, you know. 'Course he'd like you to say, yes that is dad, you know. He could make cake or puddings, yes. Yes, he could do that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 How often did he do it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Well I suppose during the time - when he's away sick - he - he used to do more of it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 When he was around the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Yes, when he was around the house.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 What about cooking meat and vegetables?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 He - he could do that and make soup I believe. Well I could tell you a tale about the so
up couldn't I. Well of course poor people didn't often - weren't often able to buy a joint of meat. The only meat we used to have - would be - you go and ask the butcher for sixpen'orth of pieces and make a - a beef pudding. And I've known mother - 'cos r
ather a lot of us, she'd make a batter pudding and a suet pudding the same - same - same mealtime, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Would you have the pudding on its own?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Yes. I used to like the pudding on its own first and gravy without any vegetables, and then have a bit 
more - piece more pudding and more - and the vegetables after. But first - pudding on the plate and - and - no veg - just gravy and pudding and eat it. 'Course I got out of that habit a long time ago. Yes, we used to do it like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did your father do anything like washing up the dishes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Yes I think he used to do - could do that, yes, yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 And making the fire?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Yes. Oh he'd look after you well, I tell you, he used to be the first one up in the morning to light the fire and make to
ast before he went out at six o'clock in the morning. But I don't think he ate the crusts. And we used to - there weren't no - you opened a - the living room door and walked upstairs, there weren't no hall or nothing like that you see, that you open the f
ront door and see the stairs. Well, we used to listen to father had gone. They wouldn't let us down until he'd gone. Then we should - come down and get a couple of crusts off the toast and we used to come down and eat those crusts when he'd gone.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Why wouldn't they let you down 'til he'd gone?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
Well he didn't like us messing about in the way I suppose you see, liked to be on his own 'til he'd gone. Then you could come down, not until.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 So he made his own breakfast?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Your mother didn't have to make it for him?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
Well of course that was early, I mean to say might have been able to have a bit of breakfast in the field, take it with you see, as well, he would just - well it is a - I mean, it is a breakfast in a way, another way it ain}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid13902668\charrsid11678041 \rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 t, because you break your fast if you have ever such a little don't you.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did he come home for midday dinner?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Not often I don't think, I think they had to took it with 'em, especially when - when they've been harvesting, take your dinner - h
ot dinner in - in a - in a white basin and a cloth over it you know and perhaps tied in a big red handkerchief and hold it up like that and carry it did me dad. Yes, in the fields. Of course as I tell you they used to have home brewed beer in the field wi
th them. See, and I don't think he ever - they ever took tea in harvest time. No. And - there weren't these flasks. I don't think there was flasks at that time, my father never had one. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 What about repairs to the house and decorating?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 My - my 
mother used to do the paperhanging. Or whitewash ceilings. I don't think father ever did. No, mother used to - you'd buy a roll of paper for about tuppence ha'penny. And the paste as you put on, there weren't all these - posh names what you get today, was
 
made with ordinary flour. I suppose - I suppose it was ordinary flour as opposed to self rising mind you, ordinary flour that is, that stick it it never used to come off. Well some - some - sometimes you might go up and see with all these special things t
he paper is peeling off likely - here even. But my mother always used flour - to stick the wallpaper on. As I say it was only about tuppence ha'penny a roll, the cheapest, I suppose we'd have the cheapest.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Do you remember your father ever dressing or undressing you or washing you or the younger children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
No, no - don't remember him doing that, I think mother used to wash us when we couldn't - too young to wash ourselves and bath us - at the end of the week, in a - in a bath same as what mother did
 her wash - galvanized bath about - two foot eight across the top. The length of it and about - eighteen inches across the other way. Width of it sort of thing. - We used to have a bath like that, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 How often would you do that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Well I should think about - once a week, once a fortnight.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did you all do it the same night?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Well I think so, yes. Of course when we got older we didn't have the bath so much. No, no, well - it was hardly convenient was it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 There wasn't the privacy?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Can you remember your father ever taking you out anywhere without your mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
Yes. Yes, he used to - my father was going to Little Clacton, used to take us to Little Clacton to see his - mother and his brother. Which'd be my grandmother and my uncle. At Little Clacton, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 What did you do when you got there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
Well I remember - once sitting down to dinner, and having some dumplings and there was no salt cooked with them and they was small ones to what my mother used to make. Tha
t was at the aunt's on this particular occasion, not me grandmother's, I remember me grandmother lived in - St Osyth Road, Little Clacton, there was a pear tree overhanging the ditch. So a lot of the pears fell in the ditch sort of thing. Yes. I know ther
e
 was a pear tree there, that's a long time ago, and I think there's - there - I know there is, there's a - oak tree - on the corner, on a - on a little triangular piece of ground right near the - Little Clacton church and - and Rectory or Vicarage whateve
r that - called, and I think I've slight recollection of that being put there. It's not a - it's not a perfect tree today, it's crooked - got a rather short trunk and crooked. Then that's surrounded by white palings to protect it. Today.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 When you had the dumplings without salt did you ask for salt?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 I suppose so, yes. Yes, I think so, yes. Well they tasted funny so I suppose that's all, they hadn't got no salt in them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did your mother ever go out and leave your father looking after you children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
Well I - I - of course when she went to mother's meeting that wouldn't be when - when father'd be at home, he'd be at work would it. I don't remember father looking after us much, only as I say used to make us clothes out of old 'uns, and mother u
sed to get another woman, a Mrs Herbert, mother used to buy shirting - and have the shirts made and then Mrs - and Mrs Herbert used to make these shirts, like a kind of a dress - a dressmaker. Used to make mother's shirts.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 So you did get new shirts?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Oh we had new shirts, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
Can you remember when you were a little boy whether the older children looked after you at all? Took you for walks or fed you or looked after you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 No, used to play, I don't remember too young about others looking after me, no.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did you ever look after Norah or Jack when they were little?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 No, I don't quite remember that. Remember taking my nephew out in a - in a mail}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid13902668\charrsid11678041 -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 cart we used to call 'em, and then I had - and I was running with him and had him out of it. Yes.;
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Was that Arthur's child?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 No. I'm afraid that was Daisy's. And he died. He died of T.B. Oh that must be forty years ago. Long time ago.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did you have a certain time you had to be in bed or didn't that matter?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Well - I remember
 in the summertime we used to go to bed about perhaps about half past nine. And I remember - in these other essays - a mail van coming through Thorpe-le-Soken, horse}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13902668\charrsid11678041 -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 drawn - but it only looked like a little old box about a - two thirds of a cubic yard in m
easurement, and that came through there every night, I don't know about Sundays, at nine o'clock from Walton to Colchester. And I never see it come on return journey. So must - so - 'cos if they come back soon after got there I'd be abed and I never see i
t. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 In the winter was bedtime earlier?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Oh yes, we'd go to bed a bit earlier in the winter months. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did you have a candle to take up with you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Yes, used to have a candle to go up to bed with I think, yes. Weren't no torches was there, batter torches.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Were you put to bed when you were little by your mother or did you take yourself off to bed, do you remember?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Well I think we used to go off ourself on our own. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Do you remember ever being put to bed, tucked into bed and kissed goodnight?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 No, I can't remember that sort of thing, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Can you tell me how you all managed to sleep, people often used to share a bed in those days didn't they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Well - well we must have been.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 You had the three bedrooms at Beaumont didn't you?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Yes. Well I suppose the girls had one and the boys had the other one. There'd be three of us anyway. In one bed.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 And then in the other bedroom?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 There'd be the two girls, and the front bedroom - was my mother. Mother and dad, you know, 'til he died.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 You say you bathed every week or every fortnight when you were little?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Was there a regular time for having clean linen underclothes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Well when you had a bath. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Can you remember what sort of cooking equipment your mother had, was it a range in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Yes, kitchen range, yes, kitchen range, weren't none of these sort of things. None of them, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 After your father had his breakfast did you have a breakfast before you went to school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Oh yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 What did you have to eat?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
I daresay often it was porridge and bread and butter. Or a piece of toast. Bread and jam perhaps. The one thing I remember, put it - I put it in these essays - I don't know about breakfast or
 the - but we used to eat this old black treacle, they give it a different name today, I bought some more recently, it's supposed to be very healthy for the black treacle but it's under a different name, what they call it - molasses don't they, yes, I bou
g
ht some a year or two back and I'm afraid I had to throw it out. It didn't suit me tummy 'cos - I've had four abdominal operations. I've had four anyway. And that didn't suit me and that's no good a keep taking it I said there we used to have this black t
reacle, used to take a - perhaps a pound jam jar, cleaned and jam jar to the shop and buy a - for about two}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13902668\charrsid11678041  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
pen'orth get it full. And also we used to eat bread and lard. And that was nice and we enjoyed it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did you make the lard yourself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 No, no,
 used to buy it at the - buy it at the shop, and I think it was pork lard mind you. 'Cos this shop used to make sausages, my grandmother made - sausages at that shop before I was born.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 She worked there did she?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 She worked there and - and did one of uncles worked at that shop, the Memorial shop. Near the Thorpe Memorial.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 That was the one called Gains's was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 No, no, that was Maskell}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13902668\charrsid11678041 \rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 s in my day. And they used to sell coal and all. About shilling a hundredweight.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did you ever have anything different for breakfast on Sunday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
No, weren't so much for breakfast different, it'd be the Sunday always be something a bit different, there'd be soup and dumplings with and - making the soup as I think I've already told you with two}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid13902668\charrsid11678041  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 penn
'orth of bones. Either some blue - they called them blue peas or split peas, or a packet of pea flour which you could buy for a penny I believe, and boil 'em all up together, and put the dumplings in it and boil them up. Used to often have that on a Sunda
y. And then I don't know if we particular had this as I told you earlier on, we used to have beef pudding. Whether that was Sunday, I don't think that was Sunday, be in - in - in the week anytime, when you go to shop and ask for six}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13902668\charrsid11678041  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 penn'orth of pieces. Wel
l mother used to laugh, although we were poor but the people next door, they hadn't got so many children as us but you - make you think they were poorer than what we were, mother used to laugh at this old lady next door used to reckon she had six}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13902668\charrsid11678041  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 penn'oeth of pieces and that lasted all the week. Told my - telling my mother how - how she - eked that out you know, this six}
{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13902668\charrsid11678041  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 pennorth of pieces lasted nearly all the week.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Your mother thought that was funny?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Yes, she did, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Do you think you had anything different for breakfast on a Sunday or was it just the same?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Well perhaps we'd have a boiled egg occasionally.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did you have to share it or did you have one each?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Oh I don't think we ever shared egg, no. No. We had an egg, we had an egg or else we went without.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did you keep hens or pigs or anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
No, we never did, not in that time of day. I did when I - lad - I had some. But we never had none - when - when - I was young at all, but I tell you what, we did have a pig. 
And it belonged to my brother Albert. He got killed in the '14/'18 war at the battle of Looes. The mum pig had two little piglets. And the farmer says to my brother, and a young fellow named Hubbard, about his age who worked on the farm, knock those two o
n
 the head. It weren't worth - dilly-dallying about messing about with 'em was it, see. And that's how these two boys - one was me brother and one - a Mr Hubbard, young Hubbard, well they had those two pigs and of course me brother hadn't go nothing - prop
e
r to keep it in. I think we had an old chest of drawers and a bit of a - bit of a run for it, and that got out. And then my mother, 'cos we lived Abbey Street at the time, Thorpe - we went across the fields after it. This was dinner time when I was away f
r
om - we called it dinnertime, not lunch, in the midday in from school you see, in the dinner hour. And we went across towards - somewhere near a pond, we couldn't get it and I come back and I tried and I was really late for - for school, but I hadn't been
 
gone long to the school although I was late - one of the ladies were about five to six houses from us said, Mrs Hills, your pig is in our garden. And so mum - they got this little pig and put it back in the - where it should be. 'Course that - that belong
ed to me brother Albert. That weren't, you know, a family affair. And I don't think he ever kept any more.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did you keep them before the end of 1919?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 I used to have poultry. No - no - no more pigs, yes, I had poultry. But my mother told me, this 
was after I spent money on poultry, boy, she said, you make spare of spick and let go at the bunghole. Do you know what a spick is? It's a spick in the beer barrel, and - and the be}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13902668\charrsid11678041 e}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 r won't come out unless you release the air and - release that spick and l
et the air in and the beer'll come out of it. Well I made spare at the spick you see, and let go where you put the tap in which is the big hole, with my money. I - I - I bought - about fifteen birds and I spent thirteen pound on it, they told me that's a 
terrible lot of money and I've got nowhere proper to keep 'em. I mean when you're a young lad you don't realize these things do you, a waste of money to spend the money sort of thing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 What did your mother say?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 She said, boy, you let - make spare 
at the spick and let go at the bunghole. The spick is - is a little tiny sharp piece of wood, something like the bottom of that pen, and there's a little hole in the - in the - in - as the barrel lay like, in the top of the barrel and that's in there, kno
c
ked in there, and before the beer will come out you got to release it, and I suppose that'll make a little noise when that come out. Well I makes spare this little tiny hole you see with my money, and let go at the bunghole where you - where you knock the
 tap in. You call that the bunghole I think. But where you knock the tap in. There's already a cork in it but when you put the tap in you got knock it - knock the cork out I understand into the beer barrel. Now do you understand?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 So she was saying you were being stingy at the little hole?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 But at the big hole, the bunghole, you're wasteful?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
Wasteful, yes, that's what she meant. Say to my mother, shall I do this? I'd go and do it and spend the money, bought these poultry you see. And I suppose they'd already - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13902668\charrsid11678041 
they - they done a season of lay}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041  and they'd had it. You see, when the autumn come on and perhaps you hadn't got a good place to put 'em in they go to moult and they're ill, proper ill.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Were you earning your own money by then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Oh yes, if I didn't earnt the money I shouldn't have it to spend it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did you give your mother any to help with the housekeeping or anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 I always give her what I could. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Was it a regular sum you used to give her?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 No.
 Well when I used to go off I'd give her what I could. But I was earning when - from - from - from the age of about seven. Doing golf caddying. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 What hours were you working at that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Well we did - you did - if you did two rounds it'd be about
 from nine o'clock in the morning 'til five at night, if you did three it'd be 'til nine o'clock in the morning 'til perhaps - half past seven or eight. And - and - and a decent day like that you'd earn about three and three}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid13902668\charrsid11678041  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 pence - in those days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 What about school though?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
Ah well, the - you only went Saturdays and Sundays when it was school, never - never left - never run away from school to go golf caddying. Oh no, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Would you have liked to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 You liked school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Well, and you'd got to go to school you see, that'd be wrong not to go.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 When you did golf caddying did you carry those heavy bags of clubs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Yes. Then you had to watch where the - ball go, and walk to it. 'Cos the gentleman watch - or lady, whoever you'
re caddying for watch it and all mind you, but that's your job to know where that ball's gone. And - and perhaps tell the gentleman or lady which club to take. And they expect you to. But there is exception. One gentleman I was caddying for, I said - I sa
i
d, I thought you want such and such a club. He said, I'll do the thinking. So don't tell him what club to take. And another one wish for you to tell him - advise him which club to take. But on gentleman was a bit older and I had him - three months every d
ay, two rounds a day, he said, what you say goes with me laddie. If I told him a club he'd take it. What you say goes with me laddie, he called me.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 He was more friendly was he?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did you always do it for the same people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Well on these - on this occasion after I left school - I caddied for that gentleman all summer two rounds a day.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 He was very keen then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Yes, he came Sundays and all, two rounds a day.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did he live in Beaumont?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Well - no, no, Frinton-on-Sea.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 The people used to come from Frinton did they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Well they was at Frinton golf links you see. Yes. Yes, there's - there's one at Frinton, there's one at Clacton.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 How did you get to Frinton?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Well we used to walk to Kirby and - get on the tra
in at Kirby. And - perhaps the same at night, get on the train at Frinton get off at Kirby and walk the rest. To Blue Row, the place were pulled down.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 So you had to earn enough to cover your fares too?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Oh well our fares like that would be only -
 the half fare'd be a penny. At them times of day. A penny return from Frinton. To Kirby to Frinton. Well I suppose we didn't get returns, just got a single, ha'penny, I mean it's only a ha'penny.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did you go with some other boys?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Oh yes, used t
o be about - perhaps a dozen boys from Thorpe-le-Soken. But I think - starting young - after I started there young a lot more boys followed suit from Thorpe-le-Soken. I - I went before some of them were older than me didn't go. Of course the tale is if yo
u
 had read these essays - I knew from my older brother that he wants a penny. And I was ever so young, and I found a penny but it was a bad penny, I knew it was a bad penny but I held I want to go to Frinton you see. But later on, when I was a bit older, I
 
did an errand for a lady, to go up the butchers and grocers to order meat for some other woman and this lady gave me a penny, and on that day the boy next door asked me to come to go to Frinton with him, and I went to Frinton but that was a wet day. And I
 
used this penny for me fares, I knew my brother had this penny you see, and I being young - lot younger, I found a bad penny and cried, I wanted to go to Frinton with me brother, well I couldn't go could I you know, too young. However, caddy master said t
o
 me on that day, he said, you come next year mate, you're too young this year. And I went the next year. Caddying. But that turned out that first day I went there with that penny, which was wonderful penny really, what that did for me, weren't it? Took me
 
to - I knew - I knew me brother had a penny and that took me to Frinton and back from Kirby to Frinton, and from Frinton to Kirby and walk the rest, and that turned out to be a wet day, 'course nobody plays no golf hardly ever on a wet day, unless that's 
a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10486962\charrsid11678041 for}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 ee sport.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did you ever play golf yourself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
Well we used to play a little bit on the Frinton greensward. When we - when I was a boy. And more recently - and that's after I - I didn't go caddying for twenty-five years - I played a little bit o
n the - on the - on smaller course, nine hole course, with one or two of the other boys. Yes. Played a little bit, not much.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 How did you get familiar with the different clubs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Well years ago they used to be - got - got a name on them. One club h
as got more loft on it than another, different shape you see. More loft you see, like they had to lift anything up. And - and generally there was some - from about three to five what they call woods. Wooden - wooden headed clubs. And they'd have perhaps a
 
- a piece of - ebony - or ebony and ivory on the front of the club where that hit the ball, with these - with some of these wooden clubs. And - they used to be - I don't think they were named, not the wooden club, there's a driver, a brass, a backie or a 
small one. But today they call them one, two, three, four wood.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 And there are the irons too aren't there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Yes, their numbered from - one to about eight - eight or nine.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did they have names when you were a boy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Yes, they had their names on them when I was a little boy. Mashie - a mashie}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid3824328\charrsid11678041 , niblett, iron - mashie, niblet}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
t and so on, a cleak and a jigger. But today you never see a jigger, I've got an old one in the shed, what they called a jigger. But I've got no chance to play it 'cos no grass really suitable for it. All long grass.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Can you remember how often in a week you would have a bit of meat, would often several weeks go by without any meat?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Oh no, no, just have a little - once a week I suppose. Yes. Yes. We used to have a 
lot of potatoes and swede mixed and butter on - put a bit of butter on the swede, and pepper - on the swede. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 What did you have for teatime?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Well lot of - practically bread and jam I suppose. Bread and jam.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did you have tea to drink, or milk?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
Never milk. Tea. Always tea. And cocoa. But - coffee I hardly ever tasted when I was a child. But I like it today 'cos I never had it when I was little - little boy you see did I.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Would your father come home at teatime or not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Alway
s came home at teatime except harvest time and haysel time. Haysel. What they haysel, that's a second harvest sort of thing, it's a gathering of the grass which ripen and it's called hay. Green - green - haysel. Haysel. Haysel.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Is that before harvest?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
That's before harvest, oh yes, yes. Sometimes you might get a second - second crop of grass, you might have two haysels - have a second crop - crop of grass.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did your father have more food than the children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Well I suppose he did, no, no,
 don't think there was no picking and choosing. No. Well of course he'd want rather more than the children, that's all that amount to don't it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 What about rabbiting or poaching?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 He never did any rabbiting. No, never no poaching. Never used a gun to my knowledge to shoot rabbits, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 He didn't snare anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 I don't think he snared either, no. But you could buy rabbit for nine}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8612239\charrsid11678041  }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 pence. Grown up rabbit - all that for nine}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8612239\charrsid11678041  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 pence. Nine}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8612239\charrsid11678041  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 pence and a shilling.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did you buy them from people who were snaring them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Yes, you could buy 'em off people who shot 'em and - and snared 'em, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Were they strict round the Thorpe area and Beaumont area if people went poaching?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Well I suppose they - I suppose - I never known - anybody 
- well you see it in the paper sometimes, somebody had up for poaching. But I suppose anybody generally get realesed before they go, and that's O.K. ain}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8612239\charrsid11678041 \rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 t it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Do you remember your mother ever stinting herself of food so that you could have more food?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
I don't think she particularly did that, no. She would have done mind you but I don't think she had - she - we had something if that was - poor, we had something. Some - fill up with something.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did your father grow any fruit or vegetables?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
Oh yes, he had allotment. Had a garden and allotment, oh yes. I remember being so young and started talking about an onion bed I didn't know what an onion bed was. Was talking about an onion bed, I wouldn't want to lay on one of them. That just mean where
 you set the onion seed that's an onion bed.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did they ever buy vegetables?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Oh yes, you'd have to buy some.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 They grew quite a lot though did they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Oh a fair amount, you got an allotment, I suppose ten rod I don't know, about ten rod I should think, not less.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 After he moved to Beaumont did he keep his allotment?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
Yes. We had a piece of allotment up at Beaumont, ten rod. And I used to - help cultivate that. Yes. Dig that and set it, with me brothers.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did your father expect it of you or did you do it willingly?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
Well - we did it willingly. I remember when I was younger, being behind father with a little spade digging, when he come along he'd dig over it again, you - you - so you just got your hand in like, yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did you swear a lot when you were a child?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Well I suppose I did, you do, you hear other people don't you. Yes. I knew when I got older, knew - understood I didn't. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Your mother and father didn't mind you swearing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Well they didn't swear indoors. No, hardly ever my father swore indoors. Unless put out occasionally.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 But did they mind if you swore?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 I think that when I got to - to know, old enough to know that I didn't swear. That's when I was ever so young.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 But you don't remember them telling off the children for swearing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 If there was something on the table out of reach could you ask for it or did you have to wait 'til they offered it to you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 You could ask, yes. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did they train you to hold your knife and fork in a particular way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 I don't think they did then, no, we did it how we like.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did they mind how you sat?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 No, don't think that - no, don't think they did. No, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Could you bring a toy or a book or a paper to the table?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
What actually reading - we - we was that poor we didn't have a daily paper. The only paper come in the house - whether we had one on the Sunday then I don't quite remember - the only paper that come in the house would be old paper. To light your f
ire with, they'd buy old paper off the newsagents. Never had a daily paper, I don't think a - a daily paper like the Sketch, which is no longer, was a halfpenny. And of course and I think I'd better tell you and I think it was the Sketch, earlier on I tol
d
 you I remember something about Kind Edward VII's coronation day didn't I. Well as I say we were poor - we didn't have no daily paper, although it was only a ha'penny we didn't have no daily paper, I think we might have had one on a Sunday but I remember,
 either in standard three or standard four, in Miss Neville's class room, and they show us - a picture of King Edward VII laying dead, but not photograph drawn - sketched. Sketched, not drawn, sketched do you see. Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 When could you leave the table?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 When you finished I suppose. Just when you finished.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 You didn't have to wait 'til everyone had finished?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 No. Weren't all that - rigamarole.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did you have to ask permission to leave the table?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 I don't think - I don't think we did. I don't think we did, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Can you remember who served the meal?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Mother generally, unless father cooked the dinner. Which he - if mother was out he'd definitely do that. He'd serve it up.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Can you remember if you were served in a special order?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 No. No, I can't remember that, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Can you remember where the little ones like Norah sat before they could feed themselves, were they fed with you at the table?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Oh yes, yes, near to the table.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Where would they sit?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 I can't quite remember. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 You don't remember a high chair or anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 No, never remember mother having a high chair. No I don't.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Do you know what sort of people your parents hoped you would grow up to be?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Well at that time of day - there wa
s only farm work, but - as I told you earlier on, my mother went to Guys hospital with eye trouble, my mother got friendly up there with a lady named Mrs Baker. And mother had told her about me being on the delicate side and something about getting me a j
o
b. When it come to the point I didn't want to go, me other younger brother William went. Well he got a - actually went - he went to a - a boy's home where they send the boys out to work to learn cooking - waiting at table and all that sort of thing, scrub
bing pots or anything. But me brother William went and I didn't go. I didn't want to go.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did he want to go?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 He wanted to go, he went, yes. And actually he was confirmed at St Mary Abbots church - and of course this would be - just before the war
. '14/'18 war, just before the '14-'18 war.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 What did he do after he left the home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
Well he - he - he went to posh places I think doing cooking I think, yes, he - he used to always cook at home, he - he didn't stick it many years, he came home. A
nd worked on a farm perhaps you know, like a lot of 'em do. Come back from London working on a farm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 But before that he'd been a cook?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 He done cooking, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 After he worked on a farm did he ever do anything else?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 He worked on - he wor
ked on the building a little while. And when he was - the last job he ever done was on a - on the deck chairs along the sea front.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Taking the money for them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Yes. Going round with a machine and giving the ticket you know. He earned good money at that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 What sort of things did they bring you up to think in important in life or in your way of behaving?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Oh we'd go - go to Sunday school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did they tell you anything about right and wrong or didn't they talk about things?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Well you r
eally got that at school didn't we. My schoolmaster was ever so strict. Yes. And I'll tell you what, he used to - he used to play the organ - at Thorpe church. Then he was bandmaster. And I'll tell you what he wouldn't do, he wouldn't ride that bike on a 
S
unday. He'd walk, which was harder work in a way weren't it, he'd walk because - he - they reckoned that perhaps cycling was a pleasure and he wouldn't - he wouldn't ride a bike on a Sunday. And I can tell you I can - I can remember every hymn he had on a
 
Monday morning all the time I was there and he was my schoolmaster, which he was most - all my - my time at school except when I was in the infants, I can tell you every hymn he had on Monday morning. And that was only one, Holy, Holy, Holy, Lord God Almi
ghty, always had that hymn on a Monday. Monday morning, never anything else. And he used to play the organ at school of course. The organ, the church organ and he was bandmaster. I don't think Thorpe has got a band at all today.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Was it a brass band?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 A brass band, they never had none of them silver instruments. Weren't so much the go in them days I don't think.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Do you remember if your parents told you to hit back if another child hit you or did they say you shouldn't hit back?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 No, I don't think they ever did.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did they think you should hit back?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 I don't think they ever told me so. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 They didn't tell you not to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 No. I don't - no. I mean I didn't fight unless somebody aggravated me.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did they bring you up to behave in a certain way towards your brothers and sisters, how did they like you to behave towards them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Well I think my sister Lottie was - more than Nellie would tell me how to go on. Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did you quarrel with them much?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 No, we didn't quarrel amongst ourselves, no, we never }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8612239\charrsid11678041 quarrelled}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
, the children, one with the other, very little, no. Well my sister Lottie used to say we were a loving family. Yes. And of course you - if - I think if you've read the essays she was at Bonford Hall when I worked there. A long while before I did.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 What was she doing there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 I suppose she was house parlour}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8612239\charrsid11678041 -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 maid, waitress - you don't call them parlour}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8612239\charrsid11678041 -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
maid in a hotel do you, she was a - she was a waitress and housemaid I think you'd term her.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Chambermaid?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 No doubt don't they yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
Do you remember as a child if you could share your worries with anybody, were you a sort of child who worried about things, had worries and troubles?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 No, I don't think I did, I never was - schooling never
 worried me. The only thing when I first went - out to the infants school into the - into the - well the adult.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 And your father?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Yes. Just the same. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Was he strict?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 No, no, I don't think so. I know he worried 'cos once when I was
 a bit older and I tumbled over in a snowstorm he said, where is that poor boy? And when I got home he got - towel - white towel, warmed by the fire and warmed me, I don't think I'd got any gloves on. And I did suffer - one thing I did suffer with cold ha
nds, right - right until I went to work as a young man. And that's worse still and I've rid a lot of motorbikes in me time. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 How did your parents expect you to behave towards them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Well I don't know, I - I - mother always knew I'd do what I c
ould for her, when I was young if I earnt any money I give her all - give it to her all I could. I knew she needed it, if you remember and if you've read these essays, when I went a conce}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8612239\charrsid11678041 r}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 t before school and they had me on the platform to try to make water
 come out of my forehead - and I cried - and I think it was a Mrs Darwood, she gave me a penny. She said, what are you going to do with it? I said, I'm going to give that to my; mother. I knew she wanted it more than I did. Which I did do. What are you go
ing to do with it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 When they tried to make water come out of your forehead, was it a conjuring trick?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
Oh yes, something of that, yes, yes, yes, that was - of course it was, it upset me sort of thing. Whether I volunteered or they half dragged me up there I don't know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 When grown ups were talking were you allowed to join in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Well, I don't know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Can you remember taking part in conversations with grown ups?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 No, only with the older caddy boys perhaps. Don't - no, wouldn't be a lot older than me.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 But in the home, if your mother and father were talking could you join in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Yes, I suppose we could, yes. If that - if that interested us.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Sometimes in those days people used to say children should be seen and not heard?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
I know, yes. Our people - my mum and father weren't like that. No. School, standards one and two and three, I couldn't do the sums at first because - earlier on I couldn't read, couldn't read well enough to work the - what the words were to - what the s
um was all about sort of thing. But once I took a hold of the - to read what the - the sum wanted you to do I could do them. No worry to me, not schooling. No. And of course we used to always have an hours scripture. Started with the hymn and a prayer and
 then had an hours scripture.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did you go on going to Thorpe school then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 After we come to Beaumont I kept going to Thorpe school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 All the time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Walked. And if you read the essay on the first time coming home, I came home with a family
 what was already moved from Thorpe-le-Soken, they start pinching fruit off of a van and I started doing the same. Well I never did it no more after that night mind you. I never did it no more. Although - I might have gone and pinched apples or pears from
 under a tree, but never off a vehicle or in a shop. Only that one time, and of course. I followed suit of what they were doing, that's what happened ain't it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did anyone catch you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 No, nobody never caught us, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Why did you stop then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Well 'cos I knew it was wrong.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did you feel bad about it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 No, didn't feel - made me feel bad, I thought I'm not doing that no more sort of thing. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Were they ever caught do you know?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 No, I don't think so. No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 If you had been worried could you have told your mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Well yes, yes, she'd listen to us. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Was she an affectionate mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Yes. Oh yes. Yes. Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 When you were having meals could you all sit at the same table?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Oh yes, I think we all sat the same table, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did you all have your own set places?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Yes I think so, yes. I do today, I know I - I always sit here. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Were you allowed to talk during the mealtime?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Oh yes, I don't think we were stinted on that. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 You were allowed to talk?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Could you choose what you wanted to eat or did you have to have everything? If there was something you didn't like?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Oh no, no, if you didn't like anything you weren't forced to have it. But mother used to 
make a lot of - especially - near harvest time, is - is apple turnovers. I used to perhaps take - the whole apple turnover. Of course there's a - we - I didn't know at the time but a lot of pastry ain't a lot of good to you is it. I remember telling a lad
y
 I got heartburn. Heartburn, she says, so young. Of course I - tumbled to me after I was eating a lot of this pastry. That might have been years after, but what give me the heartburn was the pastry I was eating, I loved apple turnovers - how my mother mad
e them. She used to cut the top open - and - have a - a - a nutmeg grater and grind the - whole ginger onto the apple turnover and then - then beat it up. And I think she must have had a brown soft sugar. Brown rice sugar as opposed to ordinary }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8612239\charrsid11678041 crystallised}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
 white sugar and my mother's apple turnovers, the apples always looked brown. Not like my wife make hers, that look a semi green - pale greeny colour don't it. But I don't hardly - I daren't eat apple turnovers. No. No, I'm afraid - half afraid of 'em. So
metime if I didn't feel so afraid they might not hurt me.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 If you didn't feel hungry and you left your food what would they say?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Well that - that didn't often happen. 'Cos sometimes I think when you come home from school and it weren't teatime you
'd ask for piece of bread and jam. Well matter of fact I'll tell you, a lady next door called Mrs Palmer, she used to give me bread and jam. I don't remember but only knew mother telled me, and she said to me, if you don't stop swearing I shan't give you 
no more bread and jam.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Was that in Thorpe?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
In Thorpe-le-Soken, yes, Mrs Palmer. What they call the poor relief. But I don't remember it, but I remember one of my - my sister Lottie of course was a few - probably five years older than me, she said
 that they had the old relieving officer round, so many loaves of bread and she had to have 'em all at once instead of having - three times a week sort of thing you know so the bread got stale didn't it. And they used to - well perhaps I don't ought to sa
y
 - they used to call this old gentleman who was a relieving officer old dry bread. So we - I mean, he - he - if he allowed you to have anything he didn't allow you to have much on it sort of thing. Of course and when he retired he got praised for looking 
after - the business sort of thing, you know what I mean. Being careful with what they'd got to issue out. And that used to have to go to a board meeting.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 When you had a birthday would it be different from any other day when you were a little boy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
Not much. I remember - having a birthday - oh I don't know, I would be ten or eleven, I went to bed and I cried, I hadn't had no presents. I went to bed and cried. Yes. No, there weren't much like presents or that, no. 'Course you know we was talking ab
out earlier about how we got on for food, I had three uncles - in - in grocery business. Yes, and - 'course - one or the other used to at different times, specially near Christmastime, send a parcel of things. An I'm }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid8612239\charrsid11678041 telling}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041  you that one of my uncles - whe
n he left school - says to my grandfather, and I forget which uncle it was - well Baker, he says, to my grandfather, he left school at eight year old, well Baker, he says to my grandfather, you've given him what no one else can take away, a good education
.
 And he weren't only eight year old. And another time I don't quite know which uncle it was, he was at that memorial shop and of course these tradesmen, what do you call them - travellers who come round - they called them travellers, no, a traveller come 
r
ound to get the order for the groceries. He held this horse for - for this travelling man, and the man offered my uncle a penny and me uncle wouldn't have it. Well wouldn't have it for the simple reason that he thought that Mr Maskell had already paid him
 for his job, he didn't want that penny, it was dishonest to take it. So that's the stock we come from see what I mean.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 That was your mother's side?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Yes, my mother's side, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Do you ever remember having anything special to eat on a birthday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
Well don't know, the thing would be a plum pudding, not cake. Plum pudding. Oh my mother think more about a plum pudding than a cake. Oh yes. Plum pudding. Like you have at Christmas.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did you ever have a friend in to tea?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 I'm afraid we never did so much, no, no.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 If you did something your parents didn't like what happened in your family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
I don't remember father giving me a thrashing. - But what he used to say - I'll give you a master backhander, boy. That means hitting you lik
e that, the back of his hand I think - me sister likely said she got hit once and that weren't her at all. You know. She hadn't done whatever that was.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did he ever hit you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 No, I don't remember him hitting me. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did your mother ever hit you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 I don't think she ever hit me. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Do you remember her hitting the others?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
I remember her getting on to one of the older brothers, when he come home a bit worse for drink, I won't do it no more mother, sort of thing you know, he said to her.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did she hit him or just scold him?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Oh well she - she jawed him I think more than hit him.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Was there any other punishment you ever had?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 No, not - not by mother. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Or father?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 You weren't sent up to bed without supper or tea or anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 No, never - never - never got no dodge, mother and father, no, no, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
Would you say that you received the ideas you had about how to behave from both your mother and your father or was one more important than the other?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 About the same I think. Schooling. Schooling. I had good teachers like that. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 What sort of thing did they tell you about behaviour in those days, did they talk about how to behave?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Well I don't remember. I - of course you know you hear all about - sex these days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 You didn't have that in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
Well there was just something - that's what the teacher meant by don't behave like grown ups until you are grown ups. Miss Berwyn said to - to the class. Yes, she did, and t
hat's the only thing that ever heard - like that. Don't be grown ups until you are grown ups sort of thing. Yes, she did say that, and that's advice weren't it. I - I - I really loved my schoolteachers, especially that Miss Downs.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did your mother tell you about where babies came from and that type of thing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
No. No. Well I had a sister - she had this baby what I said I had out of the mailcart, and I realized soon after that. But I knew about sheep - and some other boy must have said something to m
e and that - and I knew soon after this - nephew of mine was born, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 How old were you then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Oh wouldn't be about ten I don't reckon.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Was she not married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 No, she weren't married then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Was this a worry to your mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Well must have been mustn't it. I don't remember her particular showing it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did the little boy come and live in the house with you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Yes, he come and lived in the house with us, yes. Then I think eventually he had to go to Tendring when they couldn'
t cope with him. To Tendring - well -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 To the work house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
Well more - wasn't - it was the infirmary where - where he went. There always was a separate part, a work house and an infirmary part. Yes, my father went there when he was a young - fairl
y young man. I told you - when you stood at the door, he sometimes used to vomit here at half past three in the morning, didn't I? That's why - see - to the infirmay a little while.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 How did your mother manage for money then when he was ill?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 I do
n't know, must have been - of course - but I think he might have got about ten bob benefit out of a sick club, and I suppose - she must have had a little out of the
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Can you remember what you did on Christmas Day when you were a little boy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Well
, we had oranges and we had nuts. Because I tell you me uncles perhaps had sent them. Had plenty of things like that and I used to think we was well away.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did you get together with any of your relations at Christmas?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Well, used to have an aunt lived nearby and of course she used to help my mother and help us a lot.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 In Beaumont was this?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
No, when we lived at Thorpe - and Baumont. Yes, she - she - she lived not - in the house as a maid there or cook you might call her at Handford House w
hich is at - in the house at - near school, Thorpe-le-Soken you see, she was - cook there. Yes. And I remember the only new suit we had when we were children, and I think that was a blazer jacket suit, well it was a - similar to a soldiers colour, khaki c
olour, with a blouse for the jacket which my aunt bought for us out of her money. 'Cos she - she wouldn't spend nothing herself hardly you know. And saved her money.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 She was very kind was she?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Yes. As a matter of fact -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Was he your mother's sister or your father's sister?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Mother's sister. Only sister she had. Three brothers.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Would this aunt come at Christmastime to you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Oh - well, yes, she would do, yes, and I think where she worked they'd send something. If they didn't send 
it they'd tell us to go round, get a plum pudding or something, or a rabbit - where she worked, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Can you remember if you had any musical instruments in the home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 No, not when I was a child, no, I did when I married, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Could anybody in your family sing well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Well I reckon a good many of us could, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 You were musical were you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Well not really but we could sing.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 If you said to him something all of a sudden while he's reading he wouldn't hear you, he'd carry on r
eading. Yes. That's the sort of books he used to have, and I used to try and read my prize books. And I remember early on sitting on the front door step - I - I wasn't old enough to understand 'em. Remember that, I couldn't understand 'em, couldn't read '
cos I couldn't understand what I was reading, too young I could read it. But I couldn't understand it you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did your mother ever read aloud to you when you were a little boy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Yes, I think she did a bit. Yes. Yes. Or she'd have us say our pray
ers I think, yes. We used to say our prayers, Little Jesus, meek and mild I think she used to say to us, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 She taught you them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 I think she did that, yes, that's a long while ago and of course that make your memory a bit hazy don't it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did she hear you say your prayers, did you say them out loud to her?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Oh yes, say it out aloud, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did your father ever read the Bible aloud to you so you should all listen?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 No he couldn't help himself I don't think he could hardly help hi
mself, he was reading that aloud because he couldn't read quietly. And he never read any other book and not a paper I don't believe, I said we never had a paper - daily paper. He - He - he wouldn't read an ordinary book.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Do you remember if there were 
any holiday, Bank Holiday outings or anything like that do you remember Bank Holidays when you were a young boy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Well yes, just the same but you'd be more busy at Frinton golf links. There'd be more playing you see on a holiday.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 You'd always go on a holiday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Yes, used to go any - all - any opportunity I had.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 From seven years onwards?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
Seven years onward. I remember an old player called Jammy - Jimmy Elliot standing there laughing at us, 'cos only laughing at me 'cos I was little I reckon. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did you go just in the summer months, what months did you go?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did you ever sing together, have a sing-song?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 I'm afraid we never did that much. My brother Harry used to sing. Older brother. My sister Lottie used to sing. And s
he's recently, a few months ago, died in St Mary's, Colchester and - when I've gone to see her, the last time I went she wasn't there, she'd fallen down and she was at Black Notley. And the other ladies in there said she sang to them beautiful. Yes. She c
ould sing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Do you remember your mother or father playing any games with you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 No, we used to play 'em, but I don't think ever mum and dad joined in, no, don't think so.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did you have playing cards in the house at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Oh, snap perhaps, I
 don't think when we was ever so young we had whist cards. I learned to play whist at Frinton-on-Sea golf caddy house. Yes, there'd be a long table about eighteen foot long, not quite as wide as this, and they used to sit on it and play cards. Well of cou
rse first of all I stood and - and watched and found out how that went. And learnt to play whist, yes. Although I don't play it now, I've only ever been to about one whist drive in my life I don't think about one or two.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 What about books, you had a few prizes from school did you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
Yes. Then I think - I had a book called Under Fire - College Queen or - True Hearts in the days of Queen Elizabeth and another one, I can't quite remember the name - about an - American boy and Scotch boy or something, bo
ys, you know. I had four. I lost the one called - Under Fire when I was in Black Notley hospital first time. They never give it me back, perhaps that'd be termed unclean, I don't know any other reason 'cos I was what you call a dirty case of perit}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8612239\charrsid11678041 oniti}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 s and of course you're - you're dirty then you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 You mean they've got to disinfect everything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
Well I don't know any other reason why they didn't give it me back. I don't think they'd let nobody else look at it, I don't think they would. I never had it no more. Of course now I'm older I don't want it do I.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Were there any other books in the house, did your mother and father have any books?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 No, my father never read - only the Bible, and he read that out aloud, my mother used to buy - the
se ladies books what come - tuppence or so a week didn't they. Woman's Own and all that sort of thing. My older brother what killed at the battle of Looes, he used to have old book called Jack, Sam and Pete. What you call a blood and thunder sort of tales
 
then. He used to have them and if you was to speak to him while he was reading he'd never hear you. He wouldn't take no notice only you. The summer months was the - most profitable. 'Course sometimes if you went in the winter months you - might go for not
hing, you see, and get no job. I have been down there and they've played with read golf balls in the snow. Yes. Red ones. You can't see a white you see in the snow so well. Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did you ever go away for a holiday when you were a young boy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 No. T
he first time I went away I was single - and I went with my sister Lottie at the Belmont Hall, to Norwich - with me brother Arthur Baker lived and his wife you see and - we got wrong the first day we was there with me sister-in-law, my sister's fault beca
u
se I think she'd already told her she'd come and meet us and we arrived at the station before me sister-in-law was there, and of course - walked - to me brother and sister-in-law's home and me sister-in-law had missed us hadn't she, and she didn't like th
a
t at all. No. Yes, and I remember once - she came over here I think when her - when her husband was in the Army. Have - having a bit of a holiday, yes. I think I walked about with her, almost as if she was my young lady sort of thing. Nothing wrong in it 
you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 She was nice was she?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
Yes, I think she was nice and as I was a child I loved to hear her talking her Norfolk Norfolk brogue you call it don't you. There's something else I ought - I - I mustn't tell you. I'll put it on paper shall I?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 How old were you then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 I was seventeen. 1917. Seventeen.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 You were going to say about your sister Lottie?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Well she - she came in bed with me and held my tummy and - not to say - and my mother - at a different time - and held my tummy. An
d I don't know which way round it was, but I told one of 'em, you did it better than the other - you know. My sister Lottie told me that since, but which way round it was I don't remember.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 You were in awful pain?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 I was in awful pain. Now is - is
 that going down? Yes. That's going down isn't it. But - I laid nine days without seeing a doctor, it was on the Thursday which would be about the seventh or eighth day, that was when the appendix must have burst and the abcess burst and I got a little ea
s
ier, and got out of bed, but that isn't particular what I want to tell you. This old cottage where we lived the three bedrooms, when I was well I could lay on the bed and hit the rafters of the roof above my head in - in the bed you see, and I thought the
n
, I'm all right when I - January 1917, there's snow on the ground with the bed open, what else I wouldn't do it, laid on the bed and - and kicked them rafters with my feet like I did when - when I was well. Would you credit it. I thought, there's nothing 
t
he matter with me, but - I got up that day, but - and I cooked myself some fried onions, which was perhaps the worst thing I could have taken, and after I had my dinner I had to get up them stairs. As on - on - on the Friday when the doctor came and he sa
id, appendicitis. Well it was perit}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8612239\charrsid11678041 oniti}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
s. Not may have been appendicitis. Well then they never bundles off me to hospital, that day, I had to wait 'til the next day. There weren't an ambulance in Clacton I don't believe. Nor in the district. But the - the 
- the Rector took me on the Saturday. In his car. Weren't laying down or nothing you know. I never grumbled. They shook like anything, an old - well I don't know if it was a Ford but it were an old class of car similar to it in that time of day. He took m
e to hospital.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Were you there a long time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
I was in there fourteen weeks, running with pus thirteen weeks. 'Cos the - the wound never healed up for thirteen - 'til the pus had done running which was about thirteen weeks. I burst the stitches - i
nside and out, had two tubes in at the first but of course later on they were useless because they were burst. And I think as likely as not by bursting that would that - that saved my life because it - it helped let the pus get away freer. And they told m
y mother when I came out, he's got a constitution like a horse. Yes. And they some of it was because I was teetotal because at seventeen I didn't ought to have - didn't ought to have been - wrong because I'd over}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid8612239\charrsid11678041 -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 drunk did I. Really. But that's what she tol
d my mother, because he's a teetotaler, it's helped him. But - I was a teetotaler which I am today. There's a little brandy in that cupboard and that's been there a long time. And a little rum and that's been there a long time. And - and when I laid there
 
like that that - that ten days I was having - hot water, a spoonful of brandy and a spoonful of sugar. Pretty - pretty often as what I liked to ask for it because I was very thirsty. 'Course actually I suppose I ought to have been kept dry. That was runni
n
g with pus thirteen weeks, I was out on - for about the fourteenth week, out of hospital. And then I couldn't - couldn't - I couldn't - I - I - I bent backed, you know, head down and back down and couldn't hardly get one foot before the other ever so slow
l
y. But after I moved about I was - I - I soon picked up. And - and I told you - earlier on about clothes, I had a little - I had a black suit and of course that was one of those cheap hairy materials, if I went like that the hair came out all over me suit
 and this come all me suit and me hair came out. And I couldn't see very well, although I ain't got no glasses, but soon as I got out of hospital and recovered my sight came - back, perfect, and my hair came all right, and - and no - no touch of}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8612239\charrsid11678041  bald}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041  head t
hen am I. Yes. I couldn't bear my hair long like some of the men like that. That'd kill me, especially - if you was outside doing a bit of hard work.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 On a Sunday were you allowed to play?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Yes, I'm afraid we were although I - my grandparents were
 ever so religious. But of course as I say she - grand - my last grandparent died in 1910. So she wouldn't have held with it, she wouldn't. Well I mean to say if I was at Frinton I'd like to go and play golf in me spare time I could, mother wouldn't say n
o
thing to me. No, she weren't fussy like that, no. I mean I was there doing the job with other people playing so won't hurt if I played would it. And also used to go and have a bathe. Matter of fact, talking about bathing - one fellow he really saved my li
f
e. I - I - and we hadn't got no bathing costumes on, at Frinton-on-Sea, but out of the town you know. Hadn't got no bathing costumes on. And I was up to my neck and I couldn't move forward. The tide was taking me out, reckon a fellow come and - caddy - an
o
ther caddy - older caddy to come and pull me out. And the same caddy boy years after, the same - same - and - had gone for a swim, a little further away from the town, he threw a cold at me, or a stone, and I looked to see who it was and I fell down and h
i
t my back on the bottom of the sea wall and the - and the actual bottom - - the wall went straight down you see, vertical, and then that went up, well I hit my back where the - where the vertical meet the - the shape of the roof of the wall and cut me hea
d open. I went in there and washed it, but that's that same fellow who saved me life threw that clod, see what I mean. Coincidence ain}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8612239\charrsid11678041 \rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 t it?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did your mother work in the house on Sunday, did she do housework and things on Sunday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Well she'd do wh
at cleaning up she'd got to do and cook. Well of course she's cooked whatever it was for Sunday, like as I tell you, soup and dumplings. Yes, generally.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 How old were you when you stopped going to Sunday school? Did you stop once you started caddying?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
Well - I think I sometimes - I still continued in the winter months, Sunday school. But - I only remember having one prize, I don't think I attended Sunday school in Beaumont very regularly. I only remember having one prize from Sunday school. And I 
think it was called the Wild Boys of Borneo. I lent - lent - lent it to young woman who - she - had lived at Thorpe-le-Soken and moved to Beaumont, I never see it no more. The Wild Boys of Borneo, she wanted that - wanted to borrow it. And I never saw it 
no more.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Would you have belonged to the choir?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
No. Well - I suppose at anniversaries I did, yes. More - when I was grown up more that is, yes, not - not as a boy. After I was married. My wife used to help in Anniversaries or services, songs in th
e chapel. And I used to - I never used to preach mind you. But I've been up in the pulpit - chairman of the young peoples service and we've got a minister there with us one day weren't always a minister, young peoples service you see, and I used to - what
 
was I saying? Reading the lesson, so - the minister says to me would I like to - to take the sermon. I said, 'cos I knew I hadn't got the capabilities to do it and I said, no thank you, you do it, you know. So he must have thought I was - a bit that way i
nclined didn't he, or else he wouldn't have asked me. I knew I wasn't capable of doing it.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 How often would you go to a service when you were a schoolchild and afterwards when you started working?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Well after I - after I married we used to go to chapel, both of us, every - once a day - Sundays.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 But when you were a teenager can you remember if you went?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Yes, I - no, we didn't stop - I didn't stop going because - because I was a bit old, no, kept going I think, oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 How did you fit it in with going caddying?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
Well on those occasions I couldn't go, it'd be more in the winter time when perhaps I'd go. Yes. Or when there used to be sermon - used to be prayer meetings I'd go in the middle of the week I think, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 They were in the evening were they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
They were in the evening, always in the evening, the prayer meetings. They don't have them today, they have what they call - Guild I think.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Were there any outings for the Sunday school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Yes. I remember going to - wi
th the - with the rest of 'em, in a farm wagon, all sitting in a farm wagon, a Mr George Rawlings driving and I suppose we had two horses. To Clacton. Had a day on the beach.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Was it nice?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Yes. And I think -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 That was from the Methodists?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Yes, and I think we went there for the Sunday school paying f}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8612239\charrsid11678041 
or to - the Kinema what's now p}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 ulled down. And - what do you call that - one of these - free market, not free market, but a similar thing there you know in this place.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Was grace ever said in your family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
No. We never said it but I know my grandparents, they never sat down to a - tiny snack without they said their grace, before and after meals, my grandparents and - and my great-uncle which was my grandfather's - grandmother's brother
. I think he used to go and see them when they were living at Elmstead.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 That was on your mother's side?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
On my mother's side, even when grandma had been dead a long while my aunt, who was at Thorpe - Landemere House, you know, that's - that was 
called Handford house at that time of day, she - she went when - when grandmother died, left that job temporarily to go and look after her uncle. And they never sat down to a little bit of snack than what they said their grace. And any - any time when - w
hen my grandmother was alive you went there and she'd want to know had you got a Bible. If you hadn't got a Bible she'd make some effort to see that you had one.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Can you remember if your father took an interest in politics at all when you were a boy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
No, I'm afraid he - he didn't understand that I'm afraid, no. I don't think he did. I think he used to vote mind you but I don't think he understood nothing much about it. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Do you know if he favoured the Liberals or the Conservatives?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 I think he favoured the Liberals. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Do you know why?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
No, I don't really know why. No. Well I think very often they did what the farmer did didn't they. Lot of people did, especially if they hadn't got much education, they did what the farmer did.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did the farmers favour the Liberals?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 I think farmers generally used to favour the Liberals. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did you think at that time that people were afraid that if they didn't follow the farmer they would lose their job or their house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Wel
l they likely - but father never lived in a tied house. No, never a tied house, no. That weren't so much in vogue then about in this district as there is today I don't think. Tied house. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Do you know if your mother took an interest in politics?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Well, she'd - she'd have a more - a better idea of it than my - than father I think. Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Do you know if she voted when women got the vote?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Yes, I think she did, yes, she would do, 'cos I mean to say - that come soon after the '14-'18 war di
dn't it. 'Cos the - Mrs - Pankhurst - made a lot of fuss about it didn't she. We used to sing, Mrs Pankhurst she's first, and Mrs Lily with a nine pound hammer in her hand. Breaking windows down the Strand, if you catch her lay her on a stretcher - knock 
her on the Robert E. Lee. Something like that. Robert E. Lee, hit her on the bottom that means I suppose, yes. She tied herself to the railings didn't she?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Was your mother Liberal too do you think?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Yes, I think she was Liberal, yes, most poor people were.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Were the farmers poor then around Beaumont?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
Well I - no, I don't know, they never - they never - they never paid much money. They never got as much help as they do today I don't think. That used to cost 'em a - lot more hours - they di
dn't pay so much for the hours work, but the - the - the farm labourers used to have to spend a lot more time - cleaning the land than what they do today because they got so many stuffs what kill it. Not only that, don't only kill weeds, that - that - tha
t
 kill the birds I think, isn't hardly any cuckoos about here now and - and if you - if you go a few more from here you're lucky if you see one pair of partridges. Because I've never been partridge shooting but I like to see a partridge, when you see a - s
e
e a whole gang fly up when they're young and - and you get later on in the season you see 'em pair off, go two - in twos. You don't see 'em. I think - this last twelve month I've seen two pair. And - and - and that's a bit extraordinary. The pest they put
 on - on the - you don't see no frogs. Whatever they put on the land kill 'em I reckon. Get in the brooks.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Do you remember if your father ever took part in sport, you wrote in your essay about quoits?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Yes, father never took part in that. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 But you remember men playing it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
Yes, my brother Albert might have done, I don't quite remember. Had a man along here, two men, two brothers in the - old people's homes in Clacton, one in one home and one in the other, they used to play quoits. One 
of 'em is my brother-in-law. He's in - he's in Glengareth. They used to play quoits.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did your father ever go to the pub?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Yes, I'm afraid he did, I remember one time he'd been there and I waiting for him before we came to Beaumont, and that was t
he Bell at Thorpe-le-Soken. 'Course and I'd had a lot of teaching on temperance at school, although I wasn't very old they teach them on temperance - I went to Bell - could hear my father in the Bell. I used to go and perhaps meet him, I knew he was in th
e
re. And I got - he'd had too much that time, he'd had too much and - I was a tired of waiting, I went towards what is now Thorpe Memorial and he come walking along, two men helping him home. I cried me eyes out and all the others laughed, you know. I thou
ght that was disgraceful you know, if my teacher was to know that, you know, that's what worried me like that why I cried. But he never come - and he never done it, only once, something - I think it was sailor about there treating him you know.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 It wasn't a regular thing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 And he weren't used to having a lot I don't suppose, and that - that makes a person worse if they ain}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid8612239\charrsid11678041 \rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 t used to it. So they tell me, 'cos I don't know 'cos I never had any. Publicans beer.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did he go regularly to the pub for a drink?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 No, I don't think he did, I don't think his money run to it. No. On this occasion as I say somebody treated him.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did your mother ever go for a drink?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 No, I don't think she did, she never would have stopped - if they did they'd - t
hey'd go there and - bring it home - more. I think in these other essays - talking about drink I used to run errands for an old - for a woman named Mrs Carter. And I used to run after drink for her, as a matter of fact her husband worked for - for his fat
h
er who was a farmer and I went and sold - I went to - to bakers shop who sold eggs and got half a dozen eggs on tick and I was to take them - to old blind Lady Cotton and tell her they was new laid eggs from the farm, sell 'em to her sort of thing cheaper
 
than what she could buy them, and she hadn't - this little lady hadn't paid for them eggs herself, she got 'em on tick and perhaps she never would pay for 'em. And when I got that money go and buy beer with it. And I think I got a ha'penny out of that dea
l.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did you often do errands for people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
I often - well that lady I used to often run errands for and also - I used to run errands when there weren't no beer attached to it when I was at school, used to go to Thorpe school from Beaumont you see and - and I used to get about three}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8612239\charrsid11678041  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
pence a week, run errands in the dinner hour and - a piece of cake and a cup of drink you know. Yes, that's about all the errands I used to run, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Do you remember if there was any club that your father or mother belonged to?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
Well father used to belong to slate club I think. And - and - and as I said, the clothing club earlier didn't I. That was chiefly for the children more than herself perhaps.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did your mother ever go out and have an outing anywhere or go out to enjoy herself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Oh I think her did, her used to go with a - mother's meeting - out - out - used to go to Felixstowe, yes they did like that, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did she have any friends?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Well I suppose she did, yes, one or two or the neighbours, whoever she lived next door to.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 The neighbours were the friends?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Yes. Oh and them - them who they met at the mother's meeting.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did they go in each others houses and have a cup of tea?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 I don't think mother did come that dodge much, no. No. We don't do that, me and my wife don't do that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 In the evenings after tea, what did your mother and father usually do before they went up to bed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Well sometimes perhaps there's ironing to be done or anything like that. That's all got to be
 done, with a box iron, we put the hot iron in the fire and put it in a - in a metal box.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did they ever have any company in in the evenings or anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 No, unless - they had somebody who was visiting - relations, her sister or - her brothers or
 anything or one of me father's brothers called in. That wasn't often.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Would they sometimes have somebody for tea?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Not often. No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 When you were a child who did you play with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Well - I used to play with the children next door named
 Samuel, one time the one of 'em - got me to do something naughty, and that's when we're leaving school - and - and this girl says to me, there was a lady doing dressmaking in the window of a house she said to me, do this to 'em look, to this lady. And I 
d
id. Well I got home, had me dinner, come back to school, we were both put in the corner. I didn't know what we was put in the corner for until a little after - being in the corner punished enough, took us to this lady's - front door to apologise to her, t
hen I knew what we'd done wrong. Yes. Then otherwise isn't often I got up to anything wrong like that, no.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Where did you play with the children next door?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Well we used to play in the gutter, perhaps marbles. And bowling the hoops along the gutte
r, weren't the traffic, there was no danger in it hardly. Only thing to go by there'd be a horse and cart. Perhaps a - oh - horse - horsemen with ploughs perhaps going home or anything. They used to bowl hoops you know. Not like a few years ago they had b
ig hoops and kept jumping through them, they used to bowl 'em along the road with a bit of stick. Girls had wooden ones and boys the had iron.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did you ever play pretending you were foxes and hounds?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Yes, we used to play fox and hounds, yes, with boys that'd be, chiefly all - all boys, yes. Go and hide so they was to find us. Yes.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Can you remember what other games you played?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Well - used to play conkers. Used to play honey bee, bobbing down or something like. And - kissing in the ring. B
oys and girls, yes, I can remember at Thorpe I remember doing that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 What was the honey bees one?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Honey - honey pot sort of thing, you just bed down I think, I don't know - don't know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Like leapfrog?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Oh used to play leapfrog, oh yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Can you remember if you were allowed to get dirty when you played?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Well I'm afraid I was rather dirty. But I don't - think mother got onto me much about it. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 She was easy going was she?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Yes, yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did she ever get angry?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 No, didn't often get angry, no.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 She wasn't that type of person?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Was she placid?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did she ever tell you you should keep away from any children, certain children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 The only thing I remember her telling me - s
omething like that - the first bicycle I had - and I think I painted it - and had a new tyre too put on - I had two tyres I think put on it, and my mother'd earlier on tell me there was a passage, in that long row of houses what's pulled down called Blue 
R
ow, there's a passage there with a door to it on the roadside, she said, don't put your bike in there Fred. She says to me, my mother. I didn't hear what she say - said to me. I put my bike in that passage. Well it hadn't been in there perhaps an hour or 
s
ome little while 'til the next time I want it and I went in there and I found one tyre was flat. I went outside and I accused some of the - which I didn't ought to have done - accused some of the older boys of letting the wind out of my tyre - one of my t
yres. I went back and the other one was the same. I - and I - and on a further investigation the both tyres had been stamp - stabbed with a knife in the wall of the tyre, I never did know who done it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 You never knew?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 No. See, if I took mother's a
dvice and not put it in there it wouldn't have happened, they was jealous 'cos I'd got it you see. I should think. Else somebody was drunk, I don't know, don't know what to think, so I never did know who done it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 But you don't remember her telling you to keep away from any children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 She didn't mind who you played with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 When you were a boy did you have any hobbies?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Mostly working weren't we, yes. Hobbies.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did you have a pet or have any collections or anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
No. We never - we never allowed to keep a rabbit I don't think, anything like that. And no poultry, nothing - not when dad was - was with us like.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 After your dad died how did your mother manage for money?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Well I suppose that - I helped 
her all I could and - and - mother got a little - little bit of a pension because me brother lost - his life in the - in the battle of Looes you see, she got a little like that. And - she's got - at the time she'd two daughters working on the Bramble Isla
nd explosive factory and myself. And another - another brother William, and I suppose Ted coming on, suppose he was at work and also she got a little out of each of us sort of thing didn't she so it weren't too bad I don't think.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Can you ever remember going to a concert or to see a play or anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
Well I think I remember we had - read those essays they used to have - something like that at the Bell - a big room at the Bedll for - Thorpe - pub you know, and - and the men who ran it were
 called Flotchet and Dartnell and I believe they had - the Poor Babes in the Wood in it sort of thing. And I remembered mother - hear that being sung, Poor babes in the wood, poor babes in the wood. Something about the babes in the wood. And I used to wan
t
 to go to this concert, but either - two reasons why I couldn't go, they couldn't afford for me to go and I wasn't old enough. So I never did go to this concert. We've had concerts as - sometimes in - in - in what the - in The Thorpe Hall Clubroom, which 
is pulled down now and they're building flats on the site of it I believe now. I've had - been to concerts in there once or twice and I've seen - Punch and Judy in Thorpe schoolyard, likes of that. Thorpe school not the \{ILLEGIBLE\}
 school. I helped build the \{ILLEGIBLE\} school, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did you ever get pocket money?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
No. No, hardly ever pocket money, only what I earnt myself, it was the other way about, if I give mother money I thought I'd do that you know. Not only that we used to - run behind when I was young and run - you know horse drawn and all run behind horse}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8612239\charrsid11678041 -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 drawn brakes }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8612239\charrsid11678041 \endash }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041  horse}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8612239\charrsid11678041 -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
drawn brakes, and - horse drawn - handsome cabs they were called, I think four wheeler things, and say shout out a copper. And then I'd perhaps get six pennies, sometim
es there were sailors in 'em, sometimes the civvies. And I remember buying my father an ounce of tobacco for three}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8612239\charrsid11678041  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
pence out of the coppers I'd picked up. But you could buy an ounce of tobacco for three}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8612239\charrsid11678041  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 pence at that time of day.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did people not mind you doing that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
No. Nothing to do with nobody - but today it'd be against the law wouldn't it. Then you see another thing as I told you in the essays that - you talking about the Conservatives and Liberals a little while ago - we used to have a rough 
band. Well go out in Thorpe street with old tin cans knocking and making a aitch of a noise you know. Yes, nobody said, you can't do it sort of thing. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Was that at election times?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 At election time, yes, you know, the - the little few days - preceding the election day like. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Where did you make the rough music then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Well - walk - walk up the main High Street to Thorpe-le-Soken toward Thorpe Green.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Were you supporting one of the parties?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Well that I don't quite remember
, now talking about that - shot at a pigeon and killed a crow. You know, concerned - concerned the election. Whether the Conservative got that up or the Liberals I don't remember. Whoever - whoever it was shot at a pigeon you see and killed a crow.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 That was a slogan?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Yes, an election slogan sort of thing, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 What did it mean do you think?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 I don't quite know, I was too young to know at the time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did this rough band ever perform at other times?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 No, only at election times. They might have had it on Guy day.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 You don't remember anybody having rough music because they'd done something that offended the people?;
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 No, oh no, weren't that - weren't nothing like that. No. No. Wouldn't - were more civilised weren't we.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Was there any other sport that you took part in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
Well we used to play cricket a bit on - some of us played on Thorpe New Meadow, cricket. 'Cos I went to school, you go there in the dinner hour see. And football. Then of course we played golf on - on the Thorpe New Meadow.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 What did you play with for clubs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Well proper golf clubs, but - but -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Where did you get them from?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Oh from Frinton, Frinton golf club, well perhaps some boys had - had 'em give to them, you had to deal with them
 and get one, I've got four out there now.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 They cost a lot to buy don't they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
They tell me they cost six pound apiece. Some young fellow wanted to buy one of mine, I didn't - well I didn't know really how many I'd got, I'd got four, I mean I'd got three or four at the time, I didn't sell him one.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 How old were you when you first got that bicycle? Was you're your first bicycle?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Yes, yes, that was my first bicycle, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 How old were you when you got that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Oh I must have been - left school. Not thinking of having a bike 'til you'd left school them days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 You paid for it yourself did you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Matter of fact - when I first went to Frinton on it I couldn't jump on and off it. And I didn't know at the time but the - I'd got to
 go - I knew I'd got to go down a hill, and got to go through a gate about - think - about as wide as an ordinary house doorway. I did. The brakes weren't acting, I was going too quick, and I hit the left hand post and knocked the forks back, you know. Bu
t
 I - I got out of it cheap really, I got it mended cheap, I pushed it to Thorpe and the - Mr Hughes at Thrope put it right for me, I don't know how much it cost, but not much. Today it'd cost you at least a pound to have a pair of forks done like I - I - 
I could do a bit bicycle repair - repairing myself, but I couldn't straighten a pair of them forks. 'Cos they bend at - got - go wrong at the crown.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did you go for walks when you were a boy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 As a young man I - seventeen I did once or twice, I'd g
o with another young fellow. And we went to - have a walk round Tendring and we went to - to Baptist chapel at Thorpe, we arranged we'd go there every week but I didn't, - I mean to say, made that arrangement but it was the next week that I - was ill with
 appendicitis, so that put a stop to that. Yes, I was a making a - with another fellow in the village to walk around with him.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Is that how young people used to meet and get to know each other then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Yes, they did, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did you ever go fishing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 The only sort of fishing been is crabbing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 You wrote about that too didn't you?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
Yes I did, yes, and - yes, I went crabbing. And I got one decent size crab, a bigger one than all the others. We gets home - and the boys next door got one 
there looked about half dead and they give me that and I was fool enough to accept it. And my - my older brother Albert, who - who was still at home, he - he - he eat this big crab of mine and I got riled - angry then, and I eat this one what was - what w
as wrong. I knew it was wrong. I think I was - lost me temper and eat that one and I reckon that's how I caught diphtheria. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 You got it soon afterwards did you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Yes, that followed on. Yes. We was talking about crabbing before I ever come to B
eaumont, oh yes, we used to go and buy a piece of lights, or anything like that, an old piece of bone, and they'd - it took a hold of meat and - and you lifted up get the crab and put it in a bag, keep the bag wet with sea water. You wouldn't get a big cr
ab like you see 'em in a shop - got one as big as my first round and be biggest you'd ever get and that'd be wonderful.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did you boil them then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Boil 'em and that's - said in the paper the other reckon that's cruelty you see. Somebody grumbling ab
out it in the paper yesterday I believe. How - how you - you put 'em in boiling water. See you put 'em in to boil, that lady or whoever was writing or man said that was cruel. Reckon there's some way you can kill them first.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 You say your mother was helped a lot by this sister of hers who was a cook?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did anybody else ever help her with anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Yes, well same as I told, me uncles did but nobody else.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did anybody ever give her hand with any of her work in the house or when she was ill, did she ever get ill?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
Well - she suffered a lot with here eyes, but I don't think she ever got nobody to help - I don't know how we got on when mother went away, I can't quite remember, the daughter - sisters done it I reckon.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Can you remember your mother and father ever going out for walks and visiting people and that type of thing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 No, I can't remember 'em going out together. I can't remember 'em going out together. I suppose one would want to be at home you see.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 They didn't have any activities they did together?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Like going to - a club for old people or anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 No, there weren't nothing of that that time of day. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 What were the different social classes in the village then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 One village or the other.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Were they different at all in the kind of different social classes they had in them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
Well there was more poorer people about especially I mean - Beaumont aint altered much but Thrope-le-Soken has, that's a - that's a - grown enormousl
y with the - amount of houses what's built, there'd nothing down built here, hardly, only council houses. I mean otherwise you'd put it on two bands - count all the new places been built what's - what's not the council.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 In Thorpe there were a lot of poor people were there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
Yes, that time of the day there was, yes. And I think little girls used to go to school with pinafores on. Although, I must have been at Thorpe school and had a lot of photographs taken I don't remember - ever remember - receiv
ing one of these photographs, you know. Yes, I don't know whether they did ask me to have 'em 'cos they knew we were poor. That's only thing I can think of. Never had any of 'em. Best of my memory girls went to school with }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid8612239\charrsid11678041 pinnies}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041  on. And of course always long hair at the back, or in pigtails.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Mostly what jobs did the poor people in the village do?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
Well mostly - most of the jobs in the village like this is only farm work, if they want anything different, if they want a job in the building line's 
got to bike there to different village - or town. I biked miles, I worked at Harwich, I worked at Dovercourt, I've worked at Frinton, I walked at Walton, I worked at Clacton, I worked at Manley, Mistley, Weeley, all over the place. Beaumont, Thorpe.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 What other social classes were there in the village in Thorpe? What about people who kept shops, did they have much more money?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Well they was - we always reckoned they was better off, oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Your uncles were better off were they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 They were
 better off, but they never had shops here dear. They - they was away. Oh yes. No, there was one of 'em that - Nonington near - near Dover. One was at Hatfield Peverell and one was at Stisted. I've never seen the - seen the - the shop. That brother who we
n
t to London in - when I wouldn't go as a lad - William - he's work - he's worked - for my Uncle Fred. And he's also worked at my brother Harry had a - had a an accident, got a bit of a money and had a shop, and my - and this brother William - worked there
 
because my brother William was a bit odd there, I think he left 'em in the lurch and didn't tell 'em he's coming away did this brother William. He's like that you know. He was, he's dead now dear. Mind you, he was good in a lot of ways but - he just thoug
ht he - he'd go away from there and leave he wouldn't be - he'd go away and not tell 'em, believe he walked home when he did come from - from - Hatfield Peverell. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 In those days were there any people you were brought up to touch your cap to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
Oh always to schoolteachers and schoolmasters, yes. Or farmers, yes. If a farmer was out there hold his horse or anything like that, always touch your cap to a schoolmaster. Oh in - and schoolteachers, oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Who were the people who lived at Thrope Hall then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 People name of Simes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did you see them around?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
Well I suppose if I saw them I should - salute them, because we know they were better off than what you were sort of thing. Better off, yes. Matter of fact one of the Mr Simes' used 
to play golf. Yes. Well at least one did anyway, 'cos there was the father, an older gent, I don't remember their mother. I think since then I believe that was a - Lady Down. And then of course then they attended Beaumont church. And I believe one time I 
met the - General Down walking from Thorpe-le-Soken, I believe that was him but I didn't know him too well did I.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Who did the schoolteachers mix with in their social life, do you know?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 No, only with themselves I think. One lived at Walton. Two li
ved at - near the churchyard at Thorpe-le-Soken, it looked a bit derelict now, with the - church shaped windows at the top you know, Gothic ain}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8612239\charrsid11678041 \rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 t it. I ought to know being a bricklayer. Think you call that Gothic. Got windows like that one thing with a - lead window panes I believe, which are very expensive.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 How were you taught to treat the clergyman?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Oh supposed to touch your cap at him anyway, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Was there anybody you called sir?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Yes, I was saying I would call anybody sir. At least - at least a tramp as I would the King of England, don't make no difference to me.

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 You were brought up that way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Oh yes, I think so.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did you do that yourself or were you brought up to do that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Well - no, I - I - come off out of my o
wn way of thinking. Specially if you don't know their name, I don't care if he's a - if he's a tramp or a King of England, if we got a King, we've got a Queen haven't we, but it don't make no difference to me, if I didn't know him I'd say yes sir to him, 
or sometimes I know I've been choked off for saying sir. Oh when I work they don't - the manager don't want you calling him sir, call him his Christian name, and the under}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8612239\charrsid11678041 -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 manager call him his Christian name. That was early on I couldn't help get in - out t
he way of it, I'd been used to saying it always you see, yes sir, yes madam - or anything you know, got so used to it throughout the years that - I can't hardly help it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Do you remember women or girls curtseying to people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 No. No, I never remember seeing that, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
Would you say that there was any difference between the people who went to the Church of England and the people who went to the Methodist chapel?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Not much difference.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Was there a different class of people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Well I think they thought they was a little better off that went to church. I think so, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 You talked about the poor people, were there any differences among the people who worked for their living?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 No, I can't see be much difference, all that little -
 they'd all get the same money, a man working in a building get a little more than a man working on a farm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did they consider themselves superior do you think in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 No, I don't think they did, not one with the other. No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 They all mixed in together?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Yes. Well you see - I don't - I've never gone to pubs so I don't - I don't mix myself really do I.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 But their wives would be friendly with each other?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Can you tell me if you remember seeing a policeman round Thorpe when you were a child?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did he walk around a lot in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Yes, they did.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 How do you think they treated the people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Well - if you behaved yourself they treated you all right.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Can you remember if your mother ever said to you, I'll call a policeman if you're a naughty boy, or anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
No, don't think she ever said that, tell you what they sometimes say if you're a naughty - I'll put you - you'll be put in the pit hole. Like a grave you know. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did she ever say that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 I think - I think I have heard her say it, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Was your home rented?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did you ever see your landlord?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 No, I think it was a rent}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8612239\charrsid11678041 -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 man came round. Yes, I think that was a collector sort of thing. I could tell you what his name was anyway. Lillie.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Do you ever remember anybody being described as a real gentleman or a real lady in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Well I don't know - years ago, when I was a lad a bloke used to say to me, you're a toff Fred. I worked wit
h as I say in these essays - and I stood on his head for a scaffold. And I think he was paying me a shilling a day for what I did, I was making what you call yellums for thatching your barns, and standing on his head and there weren't a bull not far away 
f
rom him, and I don't know now how I had the nerve to get on his head - to get and stand on his head. And the idea of standing on his head's to reach - to - to pull like - ropes done with creosote, that tallow, to - to hold the thatch down in you know so i
t didn't blow off here and there.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 When did he say you're a toff?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
One - he'd always say that, as a matter of fact what I'm going to tell you, talking about drink, he paid me a shilling a day, well perhaps during the week I hadn't any of the shilling - of my money, and at the end of the week he'd give me one and three}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8612239\charrsid11678041  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
pence, profit sort of thing. Well you see, he borrows a shilling off me - you see, and - and when it come - he's got some money to pay me back, instead of giving me a shilling he gave me one and three}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid8612239\charrsid11678041  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 pence. Yes, three}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8612239\charrsid11678041  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
pence - profit wasn't it. And he'd often say, you're a toff Fred. He wouldn't say you was a gentleman, he'd say you're a toff Fred. He - he called me a toff. He said, you're a toff Fred. You see he same - was the same na
me as me, surname. Was a thatcher and - and basket maker, he was, 'course he's dead.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 You don't know why he called you a toff?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Well I suppose - yes, anyway he was - he was really a bit of an old toff himself really, well educated. He's Conservati
ve I reckon and all. Yes, he was well educated, but he boozed you see. He said I like a little and often Fred. I like it little and often Fred. The beer.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did he have too much do you think?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Well - occasionally perhaps, just occasionally.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 But do you ever remember people talking about somebody being a gentleman or a lady?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Oh I don't know, not particular name - anybody in particular.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 If a person said that what would they mean?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Well, the gent - well they used to say, you never make a gentleman if you don't behave yourself when you were kids didn't they.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Do you remember thinking that your parents had to struggle to make ends meet when you were a child?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Well knew they did. I knew that, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 What did you think about it when you were a child, do you remember?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
Well as I say, I did all I could to help. Yes. I remember once when we hadn't much - much, my mother walked to Thorpe to meet me to buy some margarine. And talking about margarine, I think when I was very you
ng there was no such thing. But I don't know who to ask to verify my - what I think. 'Cos I remember my mother first didn't - wouldn't have it. And as I tell you we was poor. Now I heard my mother say concerning butter - that her parents, that's my grandp
a
rents never had only a quarter of a pound of butter a week and they was never without. And I don't believe at that time of day there weren't any margarine, I don't believe there was. The only thing we could fall back on was lard which I tell you we used t
o
 buy didn't I, and have it on your bread. And then another thing they used to buy to have on your bread was - well you eat it with bread and butter perhaps was what they call scraps. That's the fat what's been - melted down with the fact taken out of it a
n
d - and the - and the husk what remain sort of thing, scraps, what you call scraps, I don't know if you ever remember seeing 'em. You see, you know when you - you got your lard don't you? Well that was this - some fat - fat 'til that was melted down I sup
pose you see. Now that - that part what's remaining - strained the other off - is what you call scraps. That's slightly greasy you see, it left a little grease in it.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 When you first went to school how old were you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 I shouldn't think I was no mor
e than four. Well I'll tell you - I was in three rooms in the in - in the infants, and if I was there a year each that's three years ain}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8612239\charrsid11678041 \rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 t it. Then three one, two, three, four, five, six, seven, that make ten. Ten years of school when I was thirteen, I was
 only three that would make it wouldn't it. 'Course perhaps in the first infants I might have in only a few months then might I. I don't think I was much more than three like that when I first went to school. And my sister Lottie took me I reckon. She too
k me I reckon the first time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did you stay the whole day there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 I used to come home to dinner. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Even when you were living in Beaumont you still went home for dinner?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Oh no, no, no, not then, used to have to take sandwiches.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 And it was a church school in Thorpe?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Yes, I think that's called church school, yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 How long did it take you from Beaumont to Thorpe to school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Well - it take about - be there in half hour. In good weather go across for four fields 
and cut two miles out - I should think, about two miles cut it out. So get there in half hour.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 You said you liked school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Yes I did. Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 How did you feel about the teachers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 I liked the teachers. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did you ever have any teacher you disliked?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
Well there - there - when the - Mr Hendry retired, he was my schoolmaster, got another schoolmaster, well I don't say I disliked him but he seemed a bit rough at first. He said to me, don't you understand what I'm talking? I said, n
o sir. 'Cos he was a bit different you know. I'd got a cheek to say that really hadn't I. But that's just how I thought it was the truth and I tell you he never hit me, never said I said wrong.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Were you ever hit by anybody at school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Yes, I was.
 And unprovoked. One boy named - Frost hit me me in the tummy and nearly winded me. Well I suppose - well you see a boxer hit a bit low that - that nearly put him out don't it. And no reason at all this young lad named Frost, and I never done nothing to h
im, not after he hit me. 'Course he might have been a bit older and stronger than I was and I - I carried - when I come round a bit I went home. That was in the dinner hour. Best of my memory, hit me in the tummy. For no reason whatsoever. Never }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8612239\charrsid11678041 quarrelled}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041  him.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did you tell anybody?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 No, unless I told mother when I got home I suppose.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Do you remember if the teachers punished the children by caning them at school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Oh yes, yes, they used to have to have the cane.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Were you ever caned?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
Yes, I think I was only - yes, I think so, yes. One time with sums - although I'd been pretty good at it, my mind was fuddled for a minute and I didn't know which side this - to - to work the left}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid8612239\charrsid11678041  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 hand side of the numbers or the right. Our schoolmaster caned me. The schoolteacher didn't like it you know. Yes, she thought he shouldn't have caned me.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Was that the only time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 That's - well, that may be only time - I've been hit I think, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Do you remember any other punishments they gave you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
No, only - only in the sense that I told you of. We - we was rude to a lady and there was - when we - when we was in the infants, put our hands up like that, but other girl said to me - lived next door to me, do that to Mrs Pinks. - And I said, 
I done nothing Mrs Pinks. So when we got back to school we was put in the corner.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Do you remember if the girls were caned as well as the boys?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Not much I don't think, I don't remember any girl getting the cane, no. What they used to do is give 
you so many lines to write, after your school hours, yes, some used to have some lines didn't they, yes, so many lines. I must not do this, whatever it was or something like that. Ever so many times.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did your parents take an interest in your work at school or didn't they bother with that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Well my father wouldn't know much about it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 What about your mother, do you ever remember her asking you what you were doing at school or how you were getting on or anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 No, I can't remember she did, no, it's a long time ago.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Do you remember them ever going up to the school and looking at the work and meeting the teachers or anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Well there used to be inspectors come round. Do remember that and perhaps a - and inspect our work.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 You don't remember the parents coming up like they do today?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
No, the only time parents I remember coming up would be the prize giving day. When I told you I had - I had four didn't I, four books. They used to come on that particular day. A
nd - on one occasion, the schoolmaster wouldn't let my mother in because - she'd kept my sister Nellie away from school for some reason or other, I suppose mother'd got a valid reason for keeping her away from school, and he wouldn't - let my mother go to
 
this prize giving ceremony, but the infant school lady - she let mother in because she said - she wasn't nothing to do with the main schoolmaster, but - but I think - well of course that's altogether different, I think the schoolmaster come under every - 
all the children, the young and the - the - well after eleven they go to Landerene school or somewhere else don't they here.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Were the children who went to the school all from the same kind of home as yourself, farm}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid8612239\charrsid11678041  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 workers and farm labourers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Most all of 'em were, some worked at the Maltings, a few worked at the Maltings, round near Thorpe-le-Soken station.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 What sort of standard of living did they have?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Well I suppose they was a little better - little better off and of course they hadn't got so many children. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 What about the farmers' children and the tradesmen's children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
Well then - there was a - two girls - made pals with a sister. They - they used to come to school on bicycles, they're the only two that ever came to sch
ool on bicycles. And they'd got - and they come from that second green what I told you didn't I. When you come through Torpe second green I said that was. Yes, they come from there. And they used to cycle. But they're about the only two that ever had a - 
any - any - any cycles to go to school on. They all had to go on foot.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 How did their father manage to buy cycles do you think?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Well because he was a - he was a horse slaughterer. And of course if you - if you - they used to laugh and say that if 
one got a piece of meat what be a bit off - bit wrong they'd say that's Bowger's meat, you know, Mr Bowger. He's horse slaughterer. Oh he employed another man, of course he did a lot of it, that I don't really know. But he did employ a - at least another 
man and perhaps two men. So when a horse died or - or - that's ill, they had to go and collect 'em. That's how - how they were better off.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Do you remember if the teachers favoured the children from better off homes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 No I don't think they did. No. I used to think sometimes that I was favoured a bit. Yes, I daresay I was, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
Do you remember any children who the teachers gave a very hard time to, any children they were always picking on, sort of didn't like in the school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 No, I can't rem
ember, I remember one boy gave some trouble. That was when we was in the - the - the higher standards, there's three standards in the in - in the last room, the big - the big room like and older boys put, five, six and seven and perhaps ex-seven. Then it 
w
asn't many got to ex-seven. I think I stayed on in seven - when it come to the time to go up I didn't get into ex-seven, I still kept in - still perhaps I might have been in - in seven at eight - about eighteen months instead of twelve you see, all the ot
h
er - other - other standards I was in a twelve month and some - some of 'em perhaps - wouldn't go up. I remember one boy slight relation to me, cried because he didn't go up. I did. But - on all - all occasions when that come the - think it was somewhere 
near the prize giving time in May, that's this month ain}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8612239\charrsid11678041 \rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
t it, it - it - if you qualified for it you went in the next higher standard. And there was a boy, he didn't give trouble to the schoolmaster, what he done wrong I don't know. I suppose they caned - the schoolmaster punished him.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did the teachers - did the children have to have their heads inspected to see that they were clean?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Yes, that did happen occasionally, yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Do you remember if there were any gangs in the school, children who would gang up together and make a sort of a group?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
No, I don't think it ever happened like that. That only happen - between one and another and - my - I've heard my older sister say - I'm not all right with - the girl Watts, I don't quite remembe
r what her Christian name was. That girl Watts, and her father was the cowman. Well of course they might be being a cowman a seven day work and they was a bit better off like that weren't they.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 There weren't gangs representing different parts of the village or anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 No. Not - not - not to sort of fight each other, nothing like that, no. No, no rivalry, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Do you remember any children who were left out of things, who never seemed to have anybody to play with or who were left on their own
 a lot?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
No, I don't think there was. But there was one boy - he was one of these d'Murtons, he was a builders son and he couldn't talk properly. So perhaps he didn't enter games quite so much. I can remember he used to say about football, great ol' t
ie ought to winny. Not great old side, they ought to win, he used to say, great ol'tie ought to winny. Yes, talked like that, he couldn't help it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Was he teased by the other children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Well I suppose we did a little bit now and again - yes. Nothi
ng - nothing much. 'Cos our father wouldn't stand for it. He'd soon have - soon have been round to schoolmaster. Yes. One thing our schoolmaster - if we did wrong out of school he'd punish you. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Do you remember anything happening like that to any of the children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
Oh yes, and I don't - I don't particular remember anything but I know if we done anything wrong - he'd punish you at school, specially if that happened to be on a Sunday.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 You never went to any other school did you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 That's 
the only school, I ever went to. 'Cos see - as - when we moved to Beaumont I still carried on at Thorpe school. Which is known as Rolf school. Rolf school. Yes. And - standard one and two a Miss McDonald said. Come - come down off that tree Mills. I said,
 I've got a handle to my name Miss. She didn't say come down albert, you know, come down Mills off that tree. He'd got a handle to his name, 'cos he might have fell off and hurt himself, that's what the teacher concerned about I suppose.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did people usually call boys Mills then or did they use their Christian names?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 No, we - perhaps a lot - most of us got a nickname. No, never called each other by our surnames. No. They didn't call me -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Why did she call you Mills then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Well that's the s
choolteacher see. Says - says to - says to my - brother Albert, come down off that tree Mills. Those trees what run parallel with the road, though they weren't like that at that time of day, I mean me brother climbed you see, he couldn't hardly climb 'em 
could he.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 But the teachers called the schoolchildren by their surnames?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
No. Oh yes, I think they did, especially I remember - when we had a new school master and he didn't know our names, I think he would call you Mills.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 What about the womenfolk, what did they call each other, did they call each other Mrs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Well, the - the mother's of all the children sort of thing? Yes, they called Mrs Mills, Mrs Baker or whoever the - Mrs Salmon.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Not by their first names to each other?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 I don
't think so. Although there was an old boy about - well he's a man, one of the Pudney family, who wasn't right, and always put his hands in front of him like this and - and wetting - all slobbering down of 'em, he'd say to my mother, Lottie dear. He'd go 
outside the chapel and sing hymns. Knew the tunes, but wouldn't let him in.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did he have any work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Oh no, he - he - he was too - too wrong to work. Oh yes, he couldn't work. I think eventually he got put away.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 How did he manage to live then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
Well I suppose his father supported - his father was a - horseshoeing smith at that blacksmith's - run by Adsell, his father was you see, Pudney. Whether they got Parish help I suppose they did, I don't know.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Would you have stayed longer at school if you could have done?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 No, I don't think so, 'cos I knew I was - anxious to get to work to earn some money to help - help with the others.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did you ever take any part time education afterwards, evening classes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 No. No, that never came 
off I don't think, no. They talked of about having - girls used to go to cookery classes. But boys they were talking about carpentry classes but never did come off. Not in my time, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Do you have any regrets about your education?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12742591\charrsid11678041 Do you think you benefi}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 ted from attending school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Oh certainly, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 The first money you earned was the golf caddying?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 You did that at the age of seven?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 At the age of seven, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 You went one year and he said come back the next?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Your older brother was already going wasn't he?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Were any other brothers going at that time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Well a little later on - William followed me. But I don't think Ted did, me brother Ted did not, nor my brothe
r Jack, they didn't cotton onto that. But William did and he's only about fifteen months - younger than - than what I am. Or was, whatever.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Can you tell me what the caddy}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12742591\charrsid11678041 -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 master did, what his job was?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Well he - he - he'd got a - a building adjoi
ning the big caddy shed, and I remember that being built, a big house - only a little place at first, about 1907, and then they built a bigger one, and his was adjoining. With a - with a - little slip you know. Behind the door. So when they want the caddy
 
or perhaps earlier on he - he'd say, you go so and so Fred, or - or our nicknames - and you go with so and so and - he'd say - we'd say I was booked you see. Then he - perhaps call somebody - somebody with you and call 'em out to give 'em the bag of clubs
 
to go down to the tee and wait for the gentleman, the gentleman - if the gentleman was down there, hurry up, make haste, he's already down there or - he'll be down there in a minute. And perhaps he's not always down there. And our job in them times of day
 we used to have a big bucket of - or a - a - weren't actually a - a bucket but a - iron vessel to hold sand which was always damp to make the tee. The caddy}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12742591\charrsid11678041 -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 boys made - always used to make them - with the sand, after - when they drive off the tee, with the
 exception perhaps on short holes - when they need not take a wooden club, they didn't want no tee for it. But nowadays of course they've got little wooden pegs. Or sometimes they might be made of other better material, yes, a lot of 'em made with better 
m
aterial, and coloured. But some of 'em, the commoner ones were made of wood and they used to put them in themselves generally, unless there was some old gentleman - who couldn't bend and you put it in for him. His tee on - on the - on the tees. Which was 
where they drive off is called - is called the tee. And there's one tee on Frinton golf course, it's known as the pulpit tee, it's always up on the sea wall. The pulpit tee, yes. You have to walk up to it.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 You said you sometimes got two rounds in a day and sometimes three?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did he decide who was to get the rounds?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
Yes, always he decided who was - who was going to get the rounds, with the exception perhaps - you've had somebody regular and you know you're going. They don't - they do
n't come and book you at all, you know you're - and he knows you're going to have that gentleman. And if you - generally if you have a - a gentleman in the morning or a lady, and if they're playing in the afternoon the second round, you - you had them in 
the afternoon. Whether it's a lady or gent a playing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did they give you the money or did they give it to the caddy}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12742591\charrsid11678041 -}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 master?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 No, no, they had to go to the caddy}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12742591\charrsid11678041 -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 master, and - buy a ticket - in the morning used to be two tickets, and I think it used to be a white ticket and a blue ticket, one was marked one and four}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12742591\charrsid11678041  }
{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 pence - and - no, one was marked ten}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12742591\charrsid11678041  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 pence I think, ten}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12742591\charrsid11678041  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 pence, and the other four}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12742591\charrsid11678041  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 pence which was a lunch ticket. So I think - fourteen pence is one and three wasn't it? But always you had to give the ticket up to the caddy}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12742591\charrsid11678041 -}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 master and you received a penny less than what that said on it. Something like that just stopped for the caddy - helped pay caddy}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12742591\charrsid11678041 -}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 master I reckon. And - and a tip. Which in those days was - was might be about three}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12742591\charrsid11678041  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 penc
e a one round and sixpence for two. Sometimes only tuppence a round, chance times with one or two people - nixy, nothing. Well I once caddied for an old gentleman got a very heavy bag of clubs, I knew he never give no tip, and towards the end - end of the
 
round I - I said, to him, these clubs are too heavy for me, which I really didn't mean it you know, I didn't want to caddy for him in the afternoon. So when we come to the eighteenth tee to come off he said, tuppence for your courage. 'Cos I wouldn't let 
him take the clubs away from me, I said, I'll carry 'em. No, I'll have 'em. So when he come to the eighteenth tee before getting to the caddy}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12742591\charrsid11678041 -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 master he gave me tuppence, he said, tuppence for your courage.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did they ever talk to you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Some more than others. Oh yes, of course they talk to you - especially - they want to know what club to take. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did they ever talk to you about anything else? Ask you about your life, take an interest in you, you were a very little boy weren't you?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Yes, 
I suppose I was really, I grew up more when I - after - I left school I think, after I went to London. Perhaps tall - bit taller and slimmer. Slim you know but I think I got a bit taller. Yes, I think I was ever so little - really.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did anybody ever remark on this and ask you if you could manage, or did they just take you for granted?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
Oh most of it they take you for granted. I have more recently - after being twenty-five years lapse from going caddying of course and that's - might be nearly twenty
 years ago. I carried two clubs round there. Now - now one thing what you got to do, take your turn, your - when it come to people putting the ball in the hole you remove the stand of the pin, and as the ball come near you lift it up so the ball will go i
n the hole, I reckon perhaps - if you ain}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12742591\charrsid11678041 \rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
t there with the pin they can't see where the hole is you see. And it's - I think as I got too bad one of the other caddies said, I'll take all the pins, almost all the pins you know. He knew I'd got a load.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 How many caddies were there usually?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
I should think there were at least sixty in - in those days. Sixty. We - when we went to caddy boys outing there was - two - there - two carriages engaged for us, you know. So boys from Walton, Holland, Kirby and Th
orpe-le-Soken, and me, Beaumont. And one or two from even from Weeley.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 How did you get on with the other caddies?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Oh sometimes they cut up a bit rough, throw things about at you, oh yes. They liked to get a paper bag full of water and burst it y
ou see, and then - perhaps the water come over you, and throw stones, lot of windows had got - small mesh wire netting on so they shouldn't smash 'em. 'Cos the caddy}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12742591\charrsid11678041 -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 master couldn't always be out there.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 So he was in charge of sixty caddies?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Yes. At that time of day, before the '14-'18 war.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 What was he like, was he a nice person to work under?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Yes, I think he was, yes. Ex-policeman. He was an ex-policeman.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Was he strict?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Well I don't think he was too strict, or there wouldn't have been so much throwing about would there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 While you were working there when you were still at school did it alter your attitude to school at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 No. No. Didn't make no difference.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did you like the work or dislike it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 What, cadd
ying? I liked it. But I think our - our schoolteacher - in - in the bigger school, you know, in where five, six, seven standards, she said, oh you never ought to go to caddying on - on Good Friday. Disgusted. She thought you go and doing that on Good Frid
ay, give you a bit of a jeer about it sort of thing, you know, going to work - well it's more or less work ain}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12742591\charrsid11678041 \rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
t it on a Good Friday.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 You said you used to get three and three for three rounds?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Was that even when you were a very little boy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
It don't make no difference. If there wasn't much you sometimes - they had to have what they called paid second class caddy. I don't think I ever had that hardly ever at all, not second class pay - because I was little. No. I had one lady tell me
 once that I weren't worth me weight in cinder dirt, that's - that's when I first started, she was a Belgian lady. I wasn't worth my weight in cinder dirt. Her husband was a German and she was Belgian. And their name was Spiegel. And they had a son, he wa
s all right.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did some people come without their clubs and have to be lent clubs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
Not often I don't think, but they - I think they could borrow 'em. But they most always brought their own. Oh yes, I mean to say, well they like a set what they're used to.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did your bring your own sandwiches and things?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Yes, always brought - brought me own food, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Could you make tea there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 No. No, you couldn't make tea there. You could buy minerals. Which was only a penny a bottle at that tim
e of day. And of course some - a lot of it used to be manufactured at Thrope-le-Soken at that time. And that used to be made from - well water - which - that's supposed to be ever such good water. And that was run by Wright and Garrod, people by the name 
of Wright and Garrod}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12742591\charrsid11678041 \rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
s. 'Cos used to be them old ginger beer bottles with a stone in that act as a cork. Yes, well that was - a year or two back I saw one of them and one of those stone ginger beer bottles.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 You and your mother never had a regular arrangement about paying money?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 No. All according to what I - all according to what I got I - I gave her most all of it. And - and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 What about buying your clothes, after you left school what arrangement did you have about clothes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 I don't - well I suppose I had to pay for 'em more or less, yes. Just give me mother the money, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did she have the money for you for your clothes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Yes. Well I don't quite remember, I suppose - I - I know she got it that was in safe hands.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Could you wear any clothes for caddying?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
Well they liked you to be pretty smart. Really. And your boots clean. And I tell you what I remember, little boys used to wear a collar like a lace collar something like a lady, and I says to my mother, I said, take tha
t old collar off me mother, I said, look like a baby in this. And - and I had one of those celluloid collars what schoolboys used to wear. Washable. I said, take that old collar off me mother. Have an ordinary - celluloid stiff collar.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 After you left school your first job was on a farm wasn't it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Yes, and I got the sack after about three weeks I think, I was pulling the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid12742591\charrsid11678041 mangle}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 . And the farmer was left handed and my father said he set me to work left handed.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Was that difficult for you then?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
Well I didn't notice it 'cos I'd never done it before. Me father said he set me to work left handed. And I wasn't - my father was pulling beets in the same field but I wasn't near him.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 How did you get that job, was it your father's employer?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Yes, same farmer at that time of day, yes. McCray. 'Course that Scotch aint it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 There's a lot of them round here aren't there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Yes. Oh yes. One at Beaumont. Well there's one here.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 What sort of a man was he to work for?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Well - suppo
se he was all right. My brother worked there, my brother lived in the house, my brother Albert what got killed at Looes. He lived in the house, I suppose that's because he was milking so he'd always sure to be there early. 'Cos they used to milk and perha
ps take the milk to Harwich. 'Cos most all milking is done early on big farms.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did he tell you why he gave you the sack?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 No, I don't think he did.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 You said you think he was worried about you being only thirteen?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Oh that's right, becaus
e you used to have a - used to have to pay to sign. Only according to the register, in - in the school register, I was fourteen. And how I know that - it was in - when - when I was eleven, that's the first time had any medical examinations at school you s
e
e. Well they never asked - they asked the children, yes, they asked the children who was twelve. Well I wasn't, I was eleven. Right the next year come down for the medical examination, you're thirteen sort of thing, not twelve, so - one who should have ha
d
 a medical 'cos I was on - bit on the weak side earlier on weren't I, I never had no medical at school. Because in the book I was a year older than what I actually was, and that's how I come to leave without having anything - paper signed to say I'd got a
 
job, 'cos I was fourteen according to the school register, but I knew I was only thirteen. And I think - and the old lady that worked in the house at the farm - told the old farmer that I reckon or told his wife and it went from the wife to the farmer, th
at I weren't the correct age to leave school unless a - a card had been - letter or form had been signed to give me - to know I'd got a job.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 But he didn't tell you why?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 No, he didn't tell me why, no.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 He just told you one day to stop did he?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
Well he give you a week's notice. Suppose he give me a week's notice, that was the - the - the gist of it that time of day, week's notice.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 What were you paid there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 I think I had about three and sixpence a week. At Frinton caddying if I d
one well I'd earn that in one day see. So when he sacked me I did go to Frinton. What we termed regular, all the time, Sundays and all. Of course - I mean - I left school in October, winter was approaching wasn't it. There wouldn't be so much work in the 
winter but I kept there 'til the - 'til the war broke out. Then I went away to Beaumont Hall.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 How did you like the work there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Beaumont Hall? I - I liked that all right, yes. The time never dragged. Did you see it in there where I dropped the cro
ckery and - and caught it before it got to the floor? And Miss Emma said, well done Fred. She didn't say, well done Mills, well done Fred.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 What sort of hours did you have to work at Beaumont Hall?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Well I suppose that'd be from seven in the morning to about half past eight at night.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did you ever have a day off?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Yes, I think we had a day off, and I suppose an early evening.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did you live in there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Yes, I lived in. And the first time of sleeping I slept in what you call a hotel 
at Westward Ho. It was a boarding house named - named Westward Ho, not a hotel, boarding house and that was - under Beaumont people you see. And of course - that's the first time I ever heard the waves a-roaring. I don't think that disturbed me much. And 
i
f you read in that essay - that my sister was sleeping there and all and also another girl. Perhaps one of the girls who was employed at Westward Ho, but my sister was employed at Beaumont Hall like me. And I heard her say to this girl, I shall have to ki
ss him goodnight else he might cry. You know. But I shouldn't have done. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Was that your first night away from home then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Yes. Well my - never been away from home before, no. Then -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did you feel homesick?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 No. Me sister was there weren't she.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 That was Lottie?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Yes, Lottie, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 The kind of work you did there was generally helping with housework and that sort of thing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Well - wash - washing up. Dinner plates and that sort of thing, cups and saucers. Knives I suppose, teapots and urns.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Who supervised you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 I think the one called Miss Marion. Miss M}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12742591\charrsid11678041 
arion Beaumont. And she my - be}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 st of my - my supervisor. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 What was she like as a supervisor?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Well she was all right, they was all all right, yes. B
ut if you - she'd always tell you - I think all 'em would tell you if want to talk keep working. Whistle and ride sort of thing, yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Can you remember what you were paid there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 I was paid five shillings a week.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 And your keep?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 And my keep, oh yes, that was a consideration wasn't it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 What did you think of that as a wage?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Well I was fairly satisfied. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did you prefer that to the farm work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Oh yes, yes. Well of course that' wouldn't only been pulling mangolds 
if I'd kept on the farm, been other jobs. Hoeing and all that sort of thing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did you like farm work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Well, no, that was just a job.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 You preferred working at Beaumont Hall?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 At Beaumont - Beaumont Hall, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 You wrote in your book about going up to London, could you tell me a bit about that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
Yes. Well before I went to London - 'cos the gentleman was an officer, I showed you the orderlies yesterday didn't I on that postcard. He's an officer - delivered at Beaumont Hall and I u
sed to be - washing the entrance out, the floor, I think they were tiles you know, but I don't believe they are tiles today. I was there the other day visiting another old gentleman. And he used to come by every morning. I says good morning to him and he 
s
ays would I like a job in London. And eventually - he gave me half - gold half sovereign to buy boots and perhaps a neck tie or something like that, 'cos you could by a rather a lot with half a sovereign in those days. And he gave me that in the billiard 
r
oom. And - when it comes more the time to - to go to London, South Kensington - he have me a golden sovereign for me fare. So I gets the ticket and my sister bottie comes down to the station with me and a girl named; Bertha Palmer. And I'd got to call, I 
t
hink you might have read it in that essay, I'd got to call at the De Vere Hotel, South Kensington, of course prior to having this house which was furnished and they was - hiring it - sort of let to them the lady and the family were staying at the De Vere 
H
otel, South Kensington, I'd got to call at the De Vere Hotel, South Kensington, in case I went to a empty house. Which was Cottishall Gardens. 4, Cottishall Gardens, off Victoria Road, not a long way away from - De Vere Hotel, not a long way from the Albe
r
t Hall. Within walking distance as a boy, but I didn't know my way. - So - I - I got off Liverpool Street station and I hired this taxi, and that was four shillings. And of course that taxi driver went, and I got in the - I knocked at the door and got in 
t
he hall and - I asked was - the lady there, Mrs - Mrs Ruston. In fact she wasn't there but this - this man said, I would like a boy like you if you don't like that job you're going to. However he called me a taxi for me and I said, how much is it please, 
b
efore ever I got in it you know, being a little old boy. Not - not when I got out, I asked how much it was before I got in it. And he said so much and - and this man said - from the De Vere Hotel, no, not so much, he's only a working class lad. So he took
 me to Cottishall Gardens from the De Vere Hotel for a shilling. No, it weren't at all bad. But after I - I mean I wasn't - paying it, it'd got to come out of that sovereign ain}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12742591\charrsid11678041 \rquote }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 t it, eventually - the missus asked me for the change out of that sovereign. Bu
t I don't think that gentleman never would have asked me for that you know, he'd never ask me for that, no. He wouldn't have asked me for that change on his own, I'm sure he wouldn't.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 What was she like?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Well I don't think she - I don't think she
 was at all nice. There was some wine - hadn't been there long, they storing wine - 'cos they was fresh there like I was you see, they were storing wine in the cupboard. She wouldn't let me put that wine in that cupboard myself. She wanted to check that a
ll in herself. And I shouldn't have touched it because I'm a teetotaler. And -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Was she the wife of this gentleman?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Yes, she's wife of this officer, there was three children. Billy, Vicky and She}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid12742591\charrsid11678041 i}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 la One little girl, and she's the youngest.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 How old were the children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
Well the boy was about - say twelve, eleven or twelve, I can tell you because I noticed he was interested in reading the paper about the wars. About the war whatever '14-'18 war.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 And girls?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 The little girl - well 
she was so young. I didn't have much to do with her really. But the little boy want me to have my hair cut like his daddy, bald headed. And - you read in there where I went to Harrods to be measured for clothes? Well I was measured at Harrods for a livery
 
suit and a going out suit. And the little boy come home, know what little children are, he said, daddy had been and got you so and so, I knew I was to have this suit and - and the livery suit. Daddy going to buy you some shirts, socks and boots and that s
ort of thing, or shoes. But mummy said no. You know, see what I mean. How - how she's the one who asked for the change out of a golden sovereign for me fare, but he - he didn't. He wouldn't have done I don't believe.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Was he ever living there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Well he's there occasionally, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 How did he treat you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
Well he was always very nice to me, when he was there I used to clean his footwear. I used to clean his footwear. I think I told you when - when I was at Beaumont Hall the - the orderlies use
d to wash - 'cos they used to get - come back - tall leather boots you know, weren't - weren't the rubber class of boot at that time of day. Leather brown boots. And - they would wash 'em and then put 'em in front of the fire to dry and then clean them.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 When you were in Cottishall Gardens, who else was working there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Cottishall Gardens. There was the cook. The parlour}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12742591\charrsid11678041 -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 maid and a housemaid. And a gardener - came - came - part time I should term it. Gardener did, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Can you tell me where you all slept and had your meals?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
Well, actually - I - we all had our meals in the kitchen. There was a - a servants room, but we didn't have our meals in it, more like a rest room. And actually that's where I slept. Only - only on a - perhaps - in wors
e bed than what we've got at home in a way, weren't no better. A camp bad which we had to be pulled up every morning. And put up before you went to bed at night.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 And where did you put your personal possessions?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Well eventually I got a tin trunk
, but how long I had before I come away I don't know. I had a fairly big tin trunk. About two foot long, about eighteen inches high and about eighteen inches wide. So what I had to bring home in it I don't hardly know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Was there a pare room in the house you could have bed do you think?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 No, no, not for me, no. No, only the rest room where the - all would be in.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 And the other servants used to sit there did they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Yes, used to sit there the same as I do. Did you read how I wrote a letter and I thought the parlour - and I was told the parlour}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12742591\charrsid11678041 -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 maid read it? Didn't I? Well, for some reason or the other the - the cook had told me that this lady pri}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12742591\charrsid11678041 o}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 r to marrying - this officer, was lower down in stature, status - status you'd call it wouldn't y
ou? Yes. She's lower down and - and I was fool enough or childlike to write in my letter and tell my mother that, so what happened - when the front door bell rang - the - the parlour}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12742591\charrsid11678041 -}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 maid said, you go and answer the door. She didn't call me Fred, she calle
d me some other nickname, I forget what it was offhand. So when I'm gone she reads my letter and she tells that woman - my mistress - what I'd wrote home and told my mother that the - until she married Mr Ruston she was lower down - n - in - being well of
f
 sort of thing, you know, and I reckon that's why I got the sack. But I got the sack - according to what she told me, for telling a lie, which one morning the - the housemaid was up late and she hadn't got time to do her work, she said, do so and so for m
e
 Fred, and I didn't - and I didn't dust the hall. The missus asked me did I dust the hall, and I said, yes, and I hadn't dusted the hall. I knew I hadn't dusted it. Hadn't had time really. For to helping the - and - and I told a like and that's why she tr
umped up the trouble a lot to - to sack me. And I think I - I said I wanted a - you know, the month's money 'cos I - she wanted me to go nearly there and then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did she give you the month's money?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Yes, she gave me - whatever that amounted to, yes.
 But it was only - it was only five shillings a week there same as Beaumont Hall. That's all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Who gave you your orders and told you what to do in that house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Oh the missus. Chiefly missus, yes, once you know what you got to do you didn't want te
lling twice. I used to have to cart the coal up, from the - from - the - the - from the bottom of the building, 'cos those sort of houses - you know, have got a floor under the floor sort of thing haven't they. What they call basements they call aint they
.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 What else did you have to do? Did you have to get up early?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Oh we used to have to get up early to - used to - clean the brasses or - or any doorknob or anything and - and - do}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12742591\charrsid11678041  the steps down with this blanc}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041  you called it didn't you or some - hearthstone, I don't kn}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid12742591\charrsid11678041 ow what you called it, to white}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 n the steps you know. I used to have to do that, and when it was cold weather - that ain}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid12742591\charrsid11678041 \rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 t a nice job I might tell you, I don't know if we had warm water or cold, I can't tell - quite remember.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 What time did you have to get started in the morning?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Well I suppose get up and make a start about seven I should think. Before breakfast, jobs to do before breakfast.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 And then you'd have breakfast?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 What was the food like?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Oh it was pretty good, the food.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 They didn't stint you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 No, well it come under cook you see. No, I wasn't stinted of food. That was very nice.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 After breakfast what did you do? Did you help the cook at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 No, no, no, didn't help the cook
, do anything in the kitchen, no, never, no, I was - had to wash up the smallest crockery. And - and clean the silver, wash the silver and any time it want cleaning clean it and put it - bai}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12742591\charrsid11678041 
ze - green baize - little bo}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 xes sort of thing so it didn't get scr
atched or anything, good silver. And I - and I used to teatime used to have to - take a silver - all silver kettle and take it up on a tray and let 'em - I think they used to heat - heat that themselves for tea.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did they have callers coming round in the afternoons?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Some times they had callers, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did you answer the door?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Yes, sometimes I did, yes, that's a page}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12742591\charrsid11678041 -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 by's job. Yes. And anybody - any came by car open the door for them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 I thought it was the parlour}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12742591\charrsid11678041 -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 maid's job to answer the door?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
Well it is if there ain't a page boy, it's more in a private house, you didn't - you don't often see a pageboy in a private house I don't think, dear, not at that time of day.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 But that was a private house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 That was a private house you see. I don't think you often hardly see - page boys. Butlers though don't you.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Were there other pageboys in the houses round about?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 I never see any. No, I don't think -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did you ever have any company your own age when you were in London?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
No, only - only - only on my own. I think the cook wanted to palm me off onto her some cousin of hers, I think I did go to - pictures with this girl once, I didn't want to go, I didn't want this girl. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 You were still quite young then weren't you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Well I was - fifteen. Until I left - about the time I left I was sixteen.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 How long were you there altogether?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 I was there about eight months I should think, some of that time we - we went to - Eastbourne.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 What did you call the missus there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Madam I think. Madam.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 What did she call you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 She called me Mills. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 What free time did you have there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 What free time? Well I suppose I had one half day off, I can't remember about in the evening. Generally th
ere's a - generally you should have an evening off you see early evening from about five.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 You don't remember if you did?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 No, don't remember if I did. But we used to have a half day and I used to go about London.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 On your own or with friends?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
Well sometimes my brother, another brother was up there, he was in a - he was up there before I was, I told you he went to do this job that I wouldn't go too. When - when he was younger. When he was about twelve, so he went to school in London, in 
South Kensington somewhere and I told you he was confirmed at - St Mary Abbots church and there's ever so many there being - confirmed. Lot of the young ladies in - all in white, and then the Bishop or - used to do 'em two - was doing 'em two at a time, b
less this they child and this they child, doing two at a time, not just one at a time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 When you were at that house did the lady take any interest in you as a person?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 No, I don't think they did, as long as you did the work that's - that's all interested that they - she wanted I think.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 She never asked you about your family or home or anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did you go to chapel or church while you were there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 No, I never went.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did she ever ask you if you were going?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 No. No
, no, wouldn't worry her. No. You've seen in there where I went into Brompton Oratory didn't you, in that book? Shall I tell you now? Well I'd heard the Brompton Oratory was such a wonderful place to visit, and I walked in there and I - I mean, a thing I 
d
on't as a rule do if I'm going to church didn't I take my cap off. I didn't do it intentionally you know, and - I don't know what - what he was, one of the men in - parson sort of a man, I don't know what you'd call him, a Roman Catholic different to Prot
estants ain}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12742591\charrsid11678041 \rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
t they, he come and just went down on - down - nearly on his knees, said, would I take my cap off. And of course I - I took that off I might tell you. But I couldn't see so much marve}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12742591\charrsid11678041 l}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 lous inside that church personally you know, unless there's somebody there to point anything out, unless the windows were wonderful.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did you ever go to any music halls?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 I went to Palladium once.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 On your own or with a friend?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 I think I went with the - with the cook's old - older sister. And she
 had a sailor brother and he used to come to visit her sometimes, I got pally with him. And he gave me one of those bands, that was a good one, what go round a sailor's hat in gold letters. So what become of it I don't know. I mean that's a thing like tha
t I'd treasure all me life if I - if I could, I don't know - when I got married or anything I don't know where it got put to do I.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 How did you get on with the parlour}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12742591\charrsid11678041 -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 maid generally, the one who told about the letter? Did she have a grudge against you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Well she must have done slightly mustn't she, else she wouldn't have done a thing like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did you ever quarrel with her?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 No, never. Never quarrelled with nobody there, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 How did the other servants treat you on the whole?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Well - they treated me all right. You see, there - there was only the parlour}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid12742591\charrsid11678041 -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 maid you see, what - out of the kitchen, was only the parlour}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12742591\charrsid11678041 -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 maid and - do you call her a chambermaid in a hotel - in a private house don't you? Housemaid - housemaid, yes, house
maid. I think they had one or two of those housemaids and they used to - she used to do some cleaning with liquid - stove polish, you know, and she split some on the carpet one time. Dear. Yes, she - she was a - she was a - you know, bit of worrying sort 
o
f girl. Of course I think that fell to that girl that - little boy to be bathed, and she'd never seen a little boy. She said - I - I don't know that only through the cook, I think the cook told me this. Said she didn't like to - to bath the little boy, so
 whether she got on all right with it after all I don't hardly know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 But he was twelve wasn't he?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 No, was one little boy only about - about eight. He's the one who's - who says to me - have your hair cut like dadd}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12742591\charrsid11678041 y}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 's - daddy was bald headed, see what I mean.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did you play with the boys at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 No. No, I don't think I did. No, there weren't time for it really, no playing about.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Were you working in the afternoon too?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Oh yes, you got to work all the - all the blooming time - som
etimes I might be - they'd got a little old pom dog. And I used to sometimes take that for a walk in Kensington Gardens.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 What time did you finish working?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Well about - about eight I think, after they'd had their dinner and things was washed up and put away.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 You helped with the washing up?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 I used to help with washing up.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did you ever wait at table?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 I don't think I did, only about once. I thought - perhaps they thought I was a bit on the nervous side you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 How did you feel when you were in that job, do you remember if you were happy or unhappy or discontented?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
Well - shall I tell you the truth? Actually I fell in love with the cook, well of course I weren't very happy. It's her fault really, not mine.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Was she older than you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
Yes, slightly, only about three years but of course she looked lot more - lot more - more grown up you know, matter of fact she - she'd already been engaged and - husband - and her - finance got killed in the war, pretty early like 
that you see, 'cos it was only 1915. So that's why this cook wanted me to palm me off with her - her niece. I went to some - some function theatre or something with this girl. Went about with her anyway.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did the cook lead you on, did she encourage you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
Well she did earlier on. Then she might have realized that I was only young and - no - no job and no money - in - at the moment was there, and didn't want me perhaps you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 So you were very sad were you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Well I was upset for some months, yes. So I was glad to get home, so it didn't worry me getting sack. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did you have anybody to tell your troubles to about how you were sad about the cook?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 No, I never told nobody.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 You kept it to yourself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 I don't know if I told me mother about it, might have told me mother, I don't remember.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 You didn't write it in a letter to her?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 I - I got - got over it eventually. No, I never wrote that in a letter. No, I didn't.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did you go out with the cook, did you ever take her out?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 No, I never took her out, never went out with her, no. I don't know, but - I think it was her sister I went to the Palladium with once.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Had you had girl friends before you went there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 No, not really, no. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 She was the first one?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 She was really the first one, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Was there anything that you particularly liked or disliked about that job, about the work and being there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 No, I don't think I liked - disliked any of it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 If you hadn't been given the sack, and apart from your feelings about the cook, the actual work, how did you feel about that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
I didn't mind the work, but - I didn't know whether I should - what the - if I could have gone somewhere else later on after I got used to it a bit and then something like that. If I was a waiter could easily have got a job couldn't you. An adult waiter.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did you call the others by their names?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Yes, Christian names, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Was the cook called missus by anybody?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 No. Mrs, oh I never noticed that, n
o. I suppose they called her cook I think, the missus called her cook. Anyway I can always remember it, the parlourmaid's name was Gertrude. And I believe she called me Nicky.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 You don't know why?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 No. Don't know why.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did they ever take you to their homes, did the cook live in London?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 No, she lived at Suffolk. No, she wouldn't take me to her home, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did any of them take you to their homes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did you ever go back to Baumont?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 No, not until I went home. No. Almost out of the question.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 What did the cook, cook on, did she have a range or a gas stove or electric?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 I think she had a fire - fire and - coal fire and range, best of my memory. Don't remember no gas.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did you have a hot dinner midday there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 What did you have for dinner there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Well - vegetables, a dough pudding and gravy I think.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Meat or not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Yes, meat.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 What did you have in the evening?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Well I suppose be similar.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 What did the family have, did they have sort of two cooked meals a day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Yes, they had two cooked meals a day.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 They didn't have a tea about five?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 They had a tea - afternoon tea. As I say, that's the time they had the silver kettle.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Then they had another meal later did they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Yes, another hot meal later, we term that dinner don't they, toffs. I call them toffs.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 You had that too did you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Yes, we'd have some when they'd finished I suppose you see. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Can you tell me what the mistress did in her spare time, she must have had a lot of leisure time with everybody to do the work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 What did she do with her time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 I couldn't hardly tell you, no. No. Sometimes she'd have people come there, and whether she went to other people's 
- you see, perhaps - they hadn't got many friends in London, they come from Devonshire. That was the Devonshire regiment. The Royal North Hussars what was at Beaumont Hall. And this officer was the one who - would you want the job sort of thing. De was on
e of the officers staying - billeted at Beaumont Hall.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 You say she came from a lower social class?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Well I - I - the cook told me so, and that's what I wrote in my letter and that's why I got the sack. I think -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Would you have thought this, were her ways different from his?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 No, no, I shouldn't have known that if I hadn't been told. No, no, it wasn't like that, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Had you met that sort of woman before?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 No. Never. I've been - seen plenty of lady golfers - that's not like living
 with 'em in a house though is it. Been plenty of lady golfers. And there's one - one lady golfer - was been mentioned on the television lately, what's her name - an old lady. Gladys Cooper weren't it? No. Yes, an actress, something of that, wasn't Gladys
 
Cooper, no, I can't think if her name was Gladys Cooper. That I can't remember for sure, that's sort of got me muddles. But one of those ladies was on Frinton Golf Links playing golf before the '14-'18 war. I think it was Gladys Cooper. It's been mentione
d lately - because she's old and still acting I think. Do you know if Gladys Cooper's still acting? Well that was her then I reckon, yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Do you know if the mistress was content with her station in life or do you think she was ambitious?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Oh no, I think she was content as far as what that go, yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 When people came to the house did they ever talk to you or take any notice of you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 No, don't think they ever - never talked to me, no, perhaps once or twice I - I - I got a little tip.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did people come for dinner parties ever?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
No, I don't think they did. Come at any time, whether dinner time or what it was I think when they did come. There weren't many came. And another job I used to have as I think I told you in the essay, used 
to have to go and call a taxi when the missus want to go out. Didn't I tell you - that - when I went to get a taxi a boy - I came on - riding - riding back on the - on the running board of a car, and some lad shouts out to me, hi, he said, you look like t
he Prince of Wales stuck up - there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 You must have quite liked that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
Yes - well, no, I didn't take - I mean, since I got older that - I realized that was a big compliment, but I didn't take no notice at the time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did you like your livery or would you rather have worn ordinary clothes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Oh yes, I liked the livery, yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 What were the other clothes you wore like?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Well I suppose they were a suit they'd bought was what you'd call salt and pepper I believe. Dark with little - whitey bits in it like.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 What did you wear when you were in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
Well afraid I - I - I had to wear the livery. Bar - bar perhaps washing up, take the jacket off. Little short jacket with buttons down the front you know. 'Course some page boys have got - double row of buttons haven't they.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Do you know if the mistress went to church?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 I don't ever think so. No, I don't think so.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did the other servants go?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 I don't - don't think they did.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Religion wasn't something they made anything of?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 No, I don't think that was. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 When you went to Eastbourne where did you live there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Darley Road, Eastbourne. Denholme Darley Road, Eastborne.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Was that a house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 A house, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 She took you with her and the governess?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Yes? And the - the governess - and a - and - and the other three - other two maids. Parlour}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid12742591\charrsid11678041 -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 maid and housemaid. Yes, we all went.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Was the work any different there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 No, pretty much the same. I don't think there was the steps to - to clean down in the morning. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did the governess live with them all the time in London too?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Who did she talk with and sit with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 I think she went and had her meals with him. Oh yes, yes, she never come in the kitchen to have her meals. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did she sit in the drawing room with them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Yes. Yes. Far as I know she did.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 They didn't have a nursemaid or a nanny?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 No. No, they never had no nursemaid, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did the governess give the children their lessons, did she teach them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 I don't think she did. I don't - don't think so.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 You think they went to school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Well the biggest one did, but I - perhaps - I don't know about the little one.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Is there anything else you can remember about that job, about the people you worked with or the work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
Well I remember when I was there we - we went - I went - made contact with my brother, he - he was in Church Road, South Kensington, so he weren't a long way away from me. We - we went - what do you call it 
- where all the glass houses are? Kew Gardens, yes. And I never did go to - Albert Hall, and I never did go to - Madam Tussauds. The money didn't run to it I suppose.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Then when - you left that job what did you do?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 I went back on a farm for some - some six months. From October to March.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 First you were at Weeley weren't you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Well then - then this farmer had got a farm at Weeley and a farm at Tendring.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 What sort of work were you doing there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Well the farm at Tendring I started 
with in the morning - there was - half a dozen cattle and about the same number of pigs. Some of the cattle was heifers and some was what we - known as steers or bullocks. And I was fat - we were fattening them up. Had to fatten 'em up - you see, and - it
 
dawned on me that two of these heifer's are in calf. Well of course they got too fat. And - was one of 'em, I don't know what happened, I think the butcher might have had the other one, that I don't know. And - the calf died you see, the poor animal was t
o
o fat wasn't it. And then I used to have to go across to - walk across the fields, the farm fields, the two farms land adjoined, and do some work over there. And one job I used to have to go and pull some white turnips and that was what you call sowing - 
b
roadcast, not in drills like rows, and I tell you that was a cold job pulling them, that was for the cows. And I - remember pulling - and always had a like a little light horse and cart to put these - white turnips in and - I was laying 'em out and the ol
d
 bull went to 'em, not eat them not yet you see what I mean, and I sort of went to drive it away, I hadn't got no stick or nothing in me hand, and that sort of come to me and - you know, with his horns, but he never come right at me. So I told the old hor
s
eman he said, that - that won't hurt you Fred, they only stick their horns up your back - side, that won't hurt you Fred. But I didn't get - I didn't wash that off them white turnips no more. And I remember too perhaps - carting up with - one job carting 
up with dirt, earth, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12742591\charrsid11678041 mangle}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
 plants, to - so the frost shouldn't get them. And I remember once going in there and - in the kitchen and helping the - the missus wash up - wash up some crockery, she said they're much - they're cleaner than what she could do 'e
m. Yes, I was used to it weren't I.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Do you remember what you were paid on that job?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Oh yes, about twelve bob a week. Yes, about twelve bob a week, yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Why did you leave that work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Well I thought I'd go to better myself to go the exp
losive factory. I suppose I earned - might have been about a pound a week there. Weren't a lot - terrible lot in it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Was there a difference in the house you had to work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 No, they was pretty much the same at that time of day. Used to have to get 
down there about half past six I believe, that explosive factory, when I worked there and I've seen the time I've walked there, when there's been snow ground you couldn't push a bike. Couldn't hardly push a bike let alone ride it. And that's terribly long
 way, about - see it's right through Great Oakley, that's six miles. Each way.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Can you describe what the work was you had to do in the factory?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Well the first job I had to do was break up some big boxes, and these boards was used as little sleepers under the small railway }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12742591\charrsid11678041 gauges}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
. That's one job as - that only lasted a day or two. And then I got working in - where they mixed - expedite - batches for expediting and that was - used to have to go into a - in a - into a mill, well I suppose stone wheel
s and a round table and the - and the wheels revolved and the table revolved and I used to have to go in there - this expedite stuff, to be ground, and when you put it in there you'd have to get to the door because that'd choke you if you kept in, but onc
e
 that started a gringing all right and settled down you could go in. And that was - used to be made expedite cartridges. And that's all done away with now, they never do that no more. And I used to have a little bit to do with two or three jobs in the cou
r
se of a day, to do with nitrate of lead, and that's somehow - lead - melted down and - and acid - does something to it somehow that's called nitic, that mean nitric acid don't it, nitrate of lead and - and that made into a liquor and that's put into woode
n
 vats and when that get cold that settle all round the wooden vat in like white crystals. And then sometimes for them to get more out of it they'd - steam it up and steam it up to get more out of it. And anyway the lead used to have to be melted down firs
t.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 When was it you were a sheeter's mate, was that at Bramble?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 No, no, it weren't Bramble, that was at Wrabness depot.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 That was after the war was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 No, no, no, during the war, I mean, them - that was built for the - for the mines to come there. Wrabness mining depot.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 That was after you'd been ill was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Yes, well that was whil}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12742591\charrsid11678041 s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 t I was at Bramble Island that time. Yes. Well of course I haven't really finished telling you about Bramble Island, I mean, when I was still at Bra
mble Island I used to have to - help with nitro-glycerine and take it up - up to what they call the A.B. House, and that's a tall - tall - used to be a tall structure on twelve by twelve timbers, wooden timbers, and there used to be another house called C
 
house, would be about - sixty yards away, and that stuff used to run down liquor in - in leaden - leaden troughs into C house, don't know what happened to that, then I suppose that was nitro-glycerine. And anyway before I was ill on that occasion - I went
 
out of that sort of chemical work, I - I was - I - I did with a man covering steam pipes which were - approximately six foot high, fairly high up, and I think there was about a - about a four inch main, and I think there was two - always two and they were
 
- I'd been helping another man cover them with asbestos, that's like in two halves and a canvas around and you stick that canvas and then put rubber right over so it - don't get the weather, that's to keep the heat in. 'Cos the more you let the heat in th
at's }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12742591\charrsid11678041 easting}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
 coal weren't it. However that man became ill and I had to do it - do it alone - and I don't know, that nearly - that was nearly my first day out that my appendicitis came over me. I kept crying and, I kept - and of course they was up high, ther
e was the boards - scaffold boards were on wooden barrels and I had to hoist myself up onto the barrels, and I got at the end I couldn't hoist myself up there no more. And I never told anybody I was ill. Waited 'til five o'clock and - endeavoured to get h
o
me. Never told anybody I was ill. I'd got to get over a big style, rather tall stile. I got - fell over when I got the other side. I picked myself up, walked across the fields and marshes, and got on my bike and lit the old oil lamp, I don't think we had 
-
 used to have a - one - you didn't have to have a rear light at that time of day I don't think, and got home and I said to my brother Ted, he's never too nice to me in the ordinary way, used to call me old jaw bones, I said, Ted, take my leggings off plea
s
e. And up them stairs I went. And there I lay 'til - 'til the tenth day. And when I - when I came back I went back to - asking for my job, I helped cover - three boilers I think it was, with asbestos, you make the same asbestos what went on the pipes - in
to a - into a paste and sort of throw it onto the boiler, that's to keep the heat in. And another time I was still down there was inside and scraping the - the fur off like forms inside a kettle only a lot worse with a hammer and chisel.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 How long did you work at the factory?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
Oh I was down there - about - fitter's mate over a twelve month. And that was when I come back from being ill you see. Well that was there that -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Were you still there when the war ended?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 No, I was at Wrabness depot
. Yes, I thought - a lot of - a lot of Bramble people - men were going to Wrabness depot and I did likewise. And - I got a job in steel erecting gang, and they termed me a - a sheeter's mate. Well sometimes I was helping - perhaps to sample principles, ir
o
n principles. And - and sometimes I was round counting corrugated iron sheets, that was in heaps all over the place, go and count 'em sort of thing. And then really the sheeter's mate part is when there's a lot of - with - with the door - with a lot of th
e
 corrugated iron buildings they was riveted before they were put up, especially the doors, well you had to get underneath a table, and that - that's an awkward job for me to do that, never ought to have had to do that, but I done it. Used to - you're unde
r
 the table with a dolly - iron dolly in your hand with a little - with a little - recess in the top of it where you - you - I'd push the rivet up, hold it up, and the man at the top puts a bur on it, like a - washer with a hole in only that's called a bur
r, and he burrs it over the rivet over while you - while I hold it up underneath the bench, table sort of thing, yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 When you left there you set up with the cycles?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 On - yes, for about fifteen months, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 When you were at Bramble Island how much free time did you get there, did you get a free day a week?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
No. No, no, you had to work there Sundays and all. Saturdays and Sundays, full day Sunday - Saturday as well as Sunday. Were working Sundays and all that time of day, during the war. Never had no half days off.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did you get overtime pay?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
Oh I suppose we did, yes, yes, they're sure to have paid you a bit of overtime. But there weren't a lot of overtime, wasn't overtime except for Sundays. I mean you had to start about half pa
st six anytime - weren't no eight o'clock business. To - to about five.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did you get any holidays with pay?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
No, never - that never - had never started. No, never no holidays with pay. No, no, no, I never had none of that 'til I was a - got that o
ff the building. Then if perchance you hadn't been to work - through being unemployed or ill - you - you don't get the - you don't get the holiday for that week when you - when you not done no work, 'cos that - that's done by stamp card affair. So you get
 the money for your holiday what's on your stamp card. How many stamps on your card.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 After you'd done the cycling you went pea picking didn't you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 I went pea picking. At Weeley I think. I'm sure, Weeley.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Then you started bricklaying?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 A
nd I started - be a builder's labourer at first. Yes, it was only way to start that. As I was on me way to Weeley I met a - a man, he weren't a - a man born in Beaumont, he said, I want a - bricklayer's labourer at Beaumont Fred. So I goes and packs up me
 
job at Weeley, draws me money and forget me - me bucket what I pick the peas in, left them in the field, and when I got back a man said to me, he said, don't think you'll be any good to us mate. Well, I said, you promised me a job and I've been and - give
 the other job - all right, I'll give you a chance. And I worked 'til dinner, he say, you'll do. Yes, and some of the time he told me not to work so hard because actually paying me less - about eight}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid12742591\charrsid11678041  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 pence an hour less money - than he was some of the other men, 'cos he's a piece}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12742591\charrsid11678041 -}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
working man you see. And he's paying those men - he said, don't you work so hard Fred, let them others do more. 'Cos they was getting the more money than I was. Ain't often a - employer tell you not to work so hard is it, especially 
a man working for himself, pieceworker. Sub-contractor they're termed.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 When did you become a bricklayer?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
Well - yes. Yes, a time before I got married I think, wait a minute. Yes, yes, the same - this same man who I worked for - bricklaying, tha
t was at Beaumont - and then that job finished. And - I got a job - on Essex Country Council, a man doing a job our way round the smallholdings altering - doing bricklaying. If I wanted - I was nowhere near perfect bricklayer, didn't know how to do the jo
b
 properly then I didn't. But I did jobs round Beaumont and Ramsey. And then - this - one of the other bricklayers, this bricklayer I worked for got another bricklayer, two other bricklayers and he was - he was - he was going to take some work at Great Oak
l
ey council houses but however there's one man cut up rough and said he'd so and so put me in the gravel pit. And said I'd cheeked him, which I hadn't, and - this man I was going to work for said he - he decided he wouldn't have nothing to do with the job 
a
fter all. He went home and told his wife, he said - and I was to go there and make mortar - with - with dried mortar, quick lime, and make mortar with it. And he went home and told his wife how that was and she said, don't you have nothing to do with that
 
job, don't send Freddy there alone to work. However the other man who I worked for first, the sub-contractor, came and I started work at Great Oakley with him. And even when I left him I - I - I couldn't - I couldn't raise a corner properly. No, he never 
put me to that really. That's all line work, well you could do that after a half hour.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 You said your wife had a daughter?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 And you went into another kind of work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 No, see, I was bricklaying, I had - I had got advanced so I was a br
icklayer and I - all the - all - then on twenty-seven, I'd had a - I'd had a - a duodenal operation and I'd been to work on some council bricklaying at - near Tollgate, Dovercourt - and then - then I went to work at Harwich - Dovercourt, further into Dove
rcourt for another builder. And I worked there all - 'til my - daughter was a fortnight old. Then I never done no more work for fourteen months. Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 After the fourteen months what did you do?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 I went to work at a hotel at Clacton, Ambleside Temperance Hotel. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 You were there for four years?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
For just under four years. I did a bit of bricklaying there. 'Cos a lot of - several of the - a man used to employ all he could - what - the summer staff in the winter and all if he could, the pr
oprietor. But they - the girl said only Freddy could lay the bricks.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 You were doing other work there too weren't you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Washing up and - I used to make the tea - and wash up the urns, make the coffee, wash up all the knives, sweep the dining rooms
, they kept you busy. Clean all the teapots and all the urns.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 After that you went to bricklaying again?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
Yes, I went to bricklaying again at Clacton. I believe that's the place where the German - German aeroplane came down and had - had a - did a lot of damage there. It came down, you know, forced down somehow I suppose.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 You went on with bricklaying then 'til 1958 did you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 'Til 1958.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 What have you done since 1958?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 I worked on the pier. Summer. Seasonal.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 You never went back to golf caddying?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 No. Never went back to golf caddying once I started on the pier, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did you just have the one daughter?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 No, was two daughters. One was a - Miss Junior Clacton Beauty Queen. 'Course I mean that's about sixteen years ag
o when she's about sixteen, and she was picked out of eighty-four girls.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Are both your daughters still alive?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Oh yes. One has got - one has - the - the beauty queen one is the youngest, hers got a boy and a girl and the boy - is that going down
 in there - and they're by adoption. Yes, the other - other daughter, she's got - three sons, the last one is about nine to ten months, I'm not quite sure - the other day was his monthly birthday, it was nine or ten months. And one is - thirteen and the o
ther one's about seventeen or seventeen and a half and he's over six foot tall. Well he's a bit on the slim side so he look taller than what he is really.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 What jobs did your daughters do?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Well they - they never did go to service in that sense like older people in my parents did, my older sisters - no, Sh}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12742591\charrsid11678041 e}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
ila - when she left school she worked at the bank. Went to the bank to work. And then when she married they didn't have married people there, she had to leave. And then she went in the Post Office
, telephonist. And she went different places for training and - got on you know, come more - pretty high in whatever she passed in sort of thing, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 What about her husband?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 He - well he was - he was a - he was a carpenter joiner but he's a joi
ner now but he's in the rubber factory. He was in the building trade, carpenter and joiner. I've worked with him.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Is he still doing joining?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Yes, still doing joinery work but in rubber. Yes, rubber factory. Clacton. And that's a - a fairly good 
paying job, especially if they do night work.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 What sort of work did she do in the bank, was she behind the counter?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Well I suppose she was behind the counter, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 What did the other daughter do?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Well she only worked on a farm. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 When she married did she go on working?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Yes, sometimes, did some - up until this last two years, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Regularly?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 And then - well - earlier on she - she worked all the winter. Gumries of Tendring. Yes, and then she's - she's been work -
 potato picking sometimes, for a few years. Or - cabbage cutting. Or - hoeing - hoeing and singling sugar beet, that one sort - done that sort of work. As a matter of fact the other younger daughter is - shortly going to work in the bank, I think that's i
n the evening, I don't know, something to do with - alterations somehow. That they want so many girls. Old employees sort of thing.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 What did her husband do?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 He's a cowman. Milks the cows.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 He's always done that has he?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Yes, he's always done it all the time we've known him, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 What did you children used to call him?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Frankie. Old Frankie Thompson.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 But not to his face?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Not to his face. No, no. As a matter of fact he said - he's under the impression that us children 
went through his gaps and - and sort of threatened to sack me father one time. In fact it weren't us at all you know, we ain}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12742591\charrsid11678041 \rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 t like children through gaps - to make 'em - gap bigger don't it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 What would you do when you met him?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Say good morning sir, you know. Yes. Is that on the go? Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Were there any grown ups you called by their first names in those days or were they all sir or Mr or Mrs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Well I remember when - when I was working on the farm at Tendring and Weeley - I said to the hor
seman, what shall I call you? Mr? He said, don't you call me Jim. And another man, that's the same man who I told you early on who I stood - when I stood on his head at Tendring - at Tendring Lodge Farm when we were thatching two barns, I asked him what I
 
should call him, do - he said, no, he didn't say quite the same way as the other man, do you call me Nathan. Nathan. Not Mr Mills. Which is my name Mills like his is you see, call me Nathan. Nathan. Not Mr Mills. Which is my name Mills like his is you see
, call me Nathan, he said. Although I was little old boy, he didn't want me to call him Mr Mills.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Why do you think they didn't want you to call them that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 I don't know, some are so fussy or - I knew that you'd got to talk older people properly ha
ven't you. You call 'em Mr so and so really, but if you don't know what his name is you can't can you. There was sometimes remind me slightly, 'cos he say, if you don't know somebody's name you'll ask them. Well it's the only way you know. And might - mig
ht be - say somebody come, you say, you seen so and so? I don't know him, you know. Well if you know you can say, yes, he's so and so. He's gone so and so.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Was your wife also in service before you met?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Yes. She was a waitress at Beaumont Hall, with my sister. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Was that her first job?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 No, she worked in a factory - a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12742591\charrsid11678041 ammunition}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041  factory at Laceton, Suffolk. That's her home town.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 That was her first job?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 That was her first - no, she - she used to go and - look after a woma
n who'd got several children, I suppose she got a little money for her. And I think -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Helping in the house you mean?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Yes, helping in the house, another - Laceton lady - woman. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 What did she do in the munitions factory, do you know?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
I don't quite know what she done, whether - something to do with shells I think. And then the war finished and as soon as that finished the work finished and they - suppose give 'em so much - week or two pay and then they left. And then they see this - 
job advertised for waitresses at Beaumont Hall, Clacton, sort of thing and - her and another girl came, but the other girl didn't stick it. She went home, she couldn't stick it - didn't like it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 After you got married did she go on working there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
No, no, no, not right away, but she did later on. Regular. She went there - when I'd been ill a long while and not earning a lot of money perhaps. We hadn't had no quarrel. She went there waitressing in the summertime, yes, one season anyway. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 And she'd lived there did she?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 She lived in, yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Has she ever done any other work?;
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
Well she's been potato - potato picking and pea - years ago more pea picking, there's not much of that today not pea picking but - and I'm afraid there
 won't be much more potato picking, they're picking up by machines. She did potato picking And she's been pea picking.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 That was seasonal?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Yes, that's only when that come on, yes, potatoes in the autumn - early autumn, late summer, early autumn.
 Potato picking. Pea - pea picking is - well in a week or two's time if there was any.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Has she ever done any other work since she got married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 No, she's only done waitressing and work in the fields a bit.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 She's not done any work in shops or anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
No, she never worked in - well, I think in a small way she did sometimes when a man had a little shop in Beaumont - while he was on a upper round, used to go in the mornings, yes, she did, yes, just a little. But - but -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Just to mind the shop?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
Just to mind the shop while the man was on a paper round a couple of hours or so. She did do that and I think I did a little while. I - when I was a little kiddie I used to want to work in a shop. Yes. And I knew my uncles had got shops and
 I thought I'd go with 'em, well I weren't about five or six you're haring to go you know. But when I did get a chance to go me other - I didn't - I turned it in again. 'Cos I - I think I - I - I was doing a job and doing pretty well. And - and the other 
brother what came home from London, he - he went to this shop.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 That was William?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
William. When I told you he was - he - he - he bit hard sort of boy, he'd - perhaps - leaving - not saying nothing about it and walked home.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 After that he came home and went to work on a farm did he?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 What did he do after he stopped working on the farm?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
For - for a little while he worked in the building trade like digging the tranches more than in the actual building. Then he was on the deck 
chairs. And - he - he - was talking about holiday, he say, they think I'm going to take their photograph. Sort of thing, how he talk. But he weren't no fool though.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Which of your brothers did you get on the best with?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Well I - I - I - I favoure
d, I don't know about getting on the best with oldest brother Harry. Because he's one who sort of used to come and go so thing, and I was always glad when he came home, Harry, older brother, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 What about the sisters, you mentioned Lottie?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Well yes, I'm rather fond of - was rather fond of Lottie, yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Was she the closest do you think?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
Yes, I think so, yes. Nellie weren't so - me sister Nellie, she weren't educated sort of thing, you know, bit duller like in education. Perhaps re
ach only about standard - I don't quite remember exactly, perhaps she would have reached only about standard three in school. We went by standards in days, I - I was - I was nearly as high as I could get in seven weren't I, but - Lottie, I suppose she was
 in six or seven, I'm not quite sure. I don't she - Lottie reached no further than six. But that don't make much different a - between those two standards.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 What jobs did Arthur do?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 He worked - I think he worked at Colmn's mustard sometime. In a Norwich. And that's where they used to do a lot of packing I think.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 He was a warehouseman?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 In the ware - Norwich, I think - it was - the Norwich warehouse. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Was he a warehouseman?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Yes, well he must have been like that mustn't he. Or he might have been I reckon he was a packer I think. A packer, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Do you know any other job he ever did?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 And - that's the only two jobs I ever known him to do was - he's always been from home, I've never known him to work on the land, was in
 the mustard - Co mustard and in the Norwich warehouse.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Those are two separate places?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Oh yes. Yes, two different class of work entirely and - two different empl
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Maud went into service from school did she?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Well - yes, I think she did,
 but as I say that's before I can remember. She go into service, yes. A little while. But I remember Maud when she was married.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 So Maud went into service?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did she marry?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Yes. She married a Clacton men, and - he was policema
n round London way somewhere. A policeman. And when he retired from the ordinary police he was police at the Hampton Court.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did she ever work after marriage?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Yes, I believe she did do. I don't know what sort of work, she used to go out to work, 
as a matter of fact she was on her way to work when - when she almost met her death. Fell down, something to do with the brain you know. Yes, she worked, during the war in some way, I think she was at Kingston. 'Cos she lived at - near Surbiton, Surrey. A
nd Kingston is in Surrey, not far from Surbiton.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 But you don't know what work she was doing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
No, I don't know what she doing, I think that was because that was a bit of a war effort to help in some way you know. Even if it was in a shop that was helping weren't it. During the war.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Daisy went into service?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did she have a husband?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 No dear. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did she always carry on in service?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 All the work she ever done was domestic. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Harry was in the grocers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 I
n the grocery line, yes. Actually he went - when he - he joined the Army, he enlisted in France. Yes, that's - so he was - in the catering corps, something like - similar to grocery when he was in France. 'Cos he was unfit for combat and any - any combata
nt service. Yes, definitely.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 What did he do when he came back from France?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
Job, got me onto the main road and I knew my way home then didn't I, so that was years before when he worked at the Beaumont - or Skid Hall it was, it was in the next - a
lmost in the next village, although that was walking distance - across fields, two or three fields. Where he did this cowman milkman's job. He was older then when he done that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 And your sister Lottie was a waitress and chambermaid at Beaumont Hall?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Was that her first job?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 No, she was round - she was somewhere - doing a job in London, somewhere near Norwood.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 In service?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Yes, something in service I believe, yes. For a month or two, year or two I mean.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 How long did she continue at Beaumont Hall?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
Well she worked as a waitress and - and general work, at Beaumont Hall 'til she married, which would be about - the same year as I married, about 1921. And after she married she done work - Beaumont Hall did their own lau
ndry - most all their own laundry - at a - at a - a house known as White House, Bockings Elm. And my sister; managed that for some thirty years I should think. Yes. Almost all the time that Beaumont Hall wanted - I mean that had been sold some long while 
a
go now, it went into different hands. But almost all the time they wanted anybody my sister managed this laundry, sometimes they had two or three other women there. And of course she had a - one of these ironers you know, a circular - an ironer, you put i
n the roll round and iron it. Not - not - that aint got - it's only the two things like ka mangle I don't think, I don't quite know how it did - that ironed the linen. The big things.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 What job did her husband do?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Well he - he - if he did any work
 it was in the building trade generally. He had worked in - on sewer trenches and that sort of thing but also had carrying and - taking up bricks and - and mortar, what they lay the bricks with.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did he have poor health?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Well, he - he got knocked
 on the head I think once - in what was known at London Road in a trench, well a - don't know if it was with a - - well it was a big piece of wood they hit posts in, something like that, hit over the head so that made him a bit wrong, so he never did have
 good health. He always had a bad cough and no doctor Did tell him to leave off smoking. And I suppose that's how he come to die. He died before - some while before my sister.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 What did Nellie do?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Well she's been in service.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did she do anything else?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Yes, she worked on the explosive factory in the - in the '14-'18 war with me other sister, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did she marry?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 What job did her husband do?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 He - he - he was a general farm labourer. Not a ploughman, a farm labourer.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 William had a lot of different jobs didn't he?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 What about Ted?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
Ted? Well he worked on a farm. 'Course - both these boys joined the Army. Ted and William. I'll have to tell you more about William in a minute. Well Ted worked at
 Beaumont Hall. On the farm. And now I think he - when he was a young man he joined the Army - he joined the Army. And - and so he was - so he was - he was going for an officers servant. Yes. As I say me brother was a bit hard but he weren't - he wasn't n
o
 fool. There's two; two group photographs. Well it's me other - me other brother's home, which I haven't mentioned. One of 'em, is - he's in the centre of the group with a machine gun. And the other one is - is in a - is in the centre of the group with a 
s
hield for running. And when a fellow was - pulling my leg, another local boy, well you know, man, he's saying that he was a champion runner. Well he must have been something it it for him to be - holding the shield what the - they're - their regiment or -
 
or part of their regiment, I don't know what they call it - call regiments and the platoons and that sort of thing, I don't know much about those procedures, what they're called, but their - their part of their - won this shield in running you see, and al
s
o he got the gun there, he knew all about the blooming - oh I forget what name - a bren gun I suppose that was called, a small gun, I don't know much about guns, I've never been in the Army on account of me being unfit for it. But he - he - he knew every 
bit of this blooming gun. That was William, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 What did Ted do after he came out of the war?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
I believe he worked for a cartage contractor. He never went to war, neither - neither of them. Only - my brother William was - some - trouble in Ireland earlier on was there. But a - but thank God he never got no hurt out of it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 You meant they joined up but they weren't sent into action?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 That - that was in between the wars you see. Brother Bill went to India, and I think he shot a - some clas
s of bird what they consider holy and - almost got into trouble about it with the natives.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 So they weren't in the Army during the war?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 They're too young you see. After the war they joined the Army.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 They both left the Army though?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Yes.
 And - then Bill he worked as I told you sometimes in the building and some - actually building house work and sometimes in trenches and all that sort of thing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 When was it Bill went into the Army, was it after he'd come back from London?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Yes, soon after - year or two after he came back from London I think, I think -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 He did farm work and then he went into the Army?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 And Ted, he went from farm work into the Army?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Into the Army.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 What did Ted do when he came out of the Army?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
He went - of course being in the Army of course some of the time he's stationed at Colchester, he worked Colchester way you see. I think he worked for a - cartage contractor, with tumbrils and horses and carts and all that sort of thing a
t that time of day. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 What rank did he reach in the army?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Only private. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 William the same?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Yes, private.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did he do anything else after he was a contractor do you know?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Ted? Well one - one job he used to do I think that was part time cleaning - cleaning up the church, at Colchester.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 That was after he finished with the contractor was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Yes, I don't know whether - what sort of work he'd doing at that time. But he did work for a cartage contractor, often - o
ften got a horse and cart, always liked horses.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 What about your brother Jack?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
Well he'd work - he'd work on the farm, he's worked on the cachement board. Cachement Board, that's the - cleaning up the rivers and all that sort of thing. And doing 
- labour - it's labouring work, yes, but that might be work sometimes got to do it according to the tide sometimes ain\rquote 
t it. Or sometimes might be just doing something to a - fleets they call 'em, like little rivers, fleets they call 'em, like cutting the 
reeds and all that sort of thing like. Well it's generally - come under the - you know, the Essex Water Board don't it. You know, for the - protection so - land don't get run over by - water perhaps.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Anything else he ever did?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 No, I don't think he did, no, only - the last job he worked on the Cachement Board.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 What did Norah do?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
Well - she - I'm afraid she didn't - she didn't very much outside service, Mother had a - somebody - girl had got a baby and - and mother had this baby and that
 was Norah supposed to look after that for - found her a little income. She's always - she's always very delicate, never did recover from being very delicate, and she died rather young. I don't know, about thirty, perhaps thirty-four, five.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 She never married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Yes she did, but she hadn't been married - might have been about thirty. She weren't very old. Yes she married.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 What was her husband's job?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 He worked at Paxman's. What job it was I don't know. Paxman's Colchester.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 This child your mother took in, was it from a lady in the village?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 No. Clacton. Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Your mother fostered it did she?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Well - she - really, yes, that's different to - just the opposite to adoption, foster, ain\rquote 
t it. Yes. 'Cos the mother used to come regular and - to see - to see this boy it was.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did they pay your mother anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
They paid my mother that's how - that's how that sort of helped me sister Norah. 'Cos she weren't well enough to keep out at a job you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 You were telling me your mother used to help an elderly lady?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Yes, on - semi-dying I call it, you know, they knew she'd soon die.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did she go every day to that house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Well she used to until I was ill myself and then this - this - of course I'd been ill some
 days, then I - was a bit better and got out of bed and walking about and mother left me. And then in a way I can't make out why she left me but of course - I was all right but after I had my dinner I - I come bad again. But she didn't go no more I might 
tell you. Not - not - not until I went away anyway into hospital, whether she did then I don't remember.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
When you were a boy before you started a full time job did you have any regular jobs you had to do round the house or in the garden or in the home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
No, I - well me father, the last year or two when I left school - weren't at any work, he was at home sick sort of thing, we used to perhaps dig the garden or help dig the garden, set it, and the same with allotment.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 You didn't have to clean boots or knives or anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
No. Mother would do that I suppose, yes. Well I don't know if I tell you one thing about - you talking about cleaning knives, if you read in those - essays how I - I used to clean the knives at Beaumont Hall and t
hey weren't knives like you have today, they was - not stainless. They used to be cleaned in a machine, and then - Miss Belmonts who were the proprietoresses said how quick I did them, and I was quick. One day I put one in the wrong way round and it cut t
h
e rubbers and I suppose that weren't no more good. But today perhaps you could have got something to have stuck that up. They said that wouldn't be no more good to - to after the war. And I suppose soon after the war - chromium plated knives came out didn
't they. See I put one knife in, I was so quick you see I put one - and - and I put one knife in the wrong way round and that cut the rubbers. And that's a German manufacture. Well they had - had rubber wheels about six inches in diameter.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 What about bread making and jam making and pickles, did your mother do anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 I think mother has made bread, and also my grandmother. But I don't think mother ever made no pickles, only jam. Made jam, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 What about wine and beer, did she make any?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
Me mother never made no - I don't remember mother ever making wine, but father, with; the other farm labourers, harvest time - used to have - they had three barrels of beer, home brewed beer. And that was nice. I didn't mind drinking that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 They made it themselves?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
Yes, these men used to make it up at - Mill House I think that was called, belonged to Harris family. I suppose that you - you need a lot of water, there's a big copper up there, that's the gist of it. And I don't suppose w
here I lived we aint got no copper of any description, but that must have been huge copper.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did your father settle with the farmer for extra money at harvest?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Yes, they used to call a settlement, they had money at the end of the harvest, otherwi
se they only earned fourteen shillings for six days, full week. No afternoons or Saturday afternoons. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Was he ever in a trade union?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 No. Never weren't nothing like that about at all dear in them days. No, never no member of no trade union.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Were you ever a member of a union?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
Oh yes. Have been once or twice. Matter of fact when you was on Wrabness depot you wouldn't be on there unless you were a member - we joined a union. They'd see you off.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Do you remember a difference in those days between craftsmen and other workers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Well the only distinction they get more money don't they.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Was there any social distinction between them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Well you see - when you come to bricklaying - it's the only trade where a bricklayer got a 
waiter sort of thing. I had to - a waiter. You know, it's looking a bit like having your food bought round, a bricklayer can't work and somebody keep bringing him the bricks and the mortar can he. He had a waiter. You see what I mean? He's a waiter, he's 
a
 bricklayer's labourer, in my opinion he's a waiter. He - he - he looks after that bricklayer and keep - he got to bring - bricklayer couldn't do nothing unless that men kept bringing the - unless he went and got 'em himself and there's no sense in that i
s there.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Was there any social distinction between them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
No. They always - friendly with each other. Yes. Though I'll tell you one thing tough I noticed - not - not many years back. There's one man who was a scaffolder, and of course he's more or
 less - a poshed up labourer, you know, bit better off perhaps you know, more qualification. Sometimes he used to lay bricks. And another brick-layer'd call him - a long handled bricklayer, much as to say he's laying bricks with a shovel, long handled bri
c
klayer because he weren't a proper bricklayer. Bit like, I don't suppose he - he - the gist of it was - he didn't like him laying bricks. 'Cos if he was in a - in a union they wouldn't let him do it either you know, kick up an awful fuss, if you - if a la
bourer was laying bricks. But it was like this other bricklayer called him a long handled bricklayer. 'Cos if - when he'd done scaffolding perhaps he'd go and lay bricks for two or three hours.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Do you remember when you were a child if some families wer
e thought of as rough and others as respectable, did people used those ways of speaking?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 
Well perhaps they might - might have almost have thought we were - bit rough. We were poor so we was slightly on - bit on the rough side. I remember - talking ab
out the kiss in the ring, we was in the kiss in the ring and one of the girls said - much as to say he's as good as what we are sort of thing, you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 She said that to you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 No, no, she said that to other girls. He's as good as what we are sort of thing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 About you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did she want to keep you out?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 No, she wanted - she - she - she wanted to kept me in didn't she like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did the other girls?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Oh no, I - no, I don't suppose - they didn't object but she said that, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did the children make any social distinctions themselves do you think?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Not often, no, not in our school. All played together. Same as the boys used to play a lot of - a bit of football in the schoolyard.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did your father ever bet or go to race meetings?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 No. No, never bet in his life I don't reckon. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did he ever do any sport or watch sport at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 No - no, I don't think so. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Darts or billiards or anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 No, don't think - no, I don't know, he used to go and have a drink but - a bit of social - sociality about that ain\rquote 
t there, mixing with people, but he never - I never heard him say he played darts.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Do you know if your mother thought of herself as belonging to a particular social class?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Well
 I suppose she thought she belonged to mothers - mother's union they called it didn't they. Yes. And they used to go on outings. Matter of fact my mother queen to Felixstowe years and years before ever I did. They used to go there nearly every year I beli
eve to Felixstowe.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Did your mother and father have the same attitude to people who were better off than they were?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Both - from both alike you mean? Oh yes, yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 They came from the same sort of background themselves?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Oh yes, exactl
y. Yes. Well, matter of fact my grandfather was supposed to be a strong man. I think it was a sack of beans, he carried from a farm opposite Thorpe police station to Thorpe Mill on his back. Yes. Although he didn't live to a great age, I think it was seve
nty-two. Didn't live to a great age like some of 'em do today.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6311765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 Do you remember people moving upwards from the poorer class, what were the richest people in the village called then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16398552 FM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8652762\charrsid11678041 They were called toffs. That's if somebody come into the village,
 yes, who do - who - they didn't do no work, you know, must have been some other - getting their money some other way, they hadn't got nobody work, they didn't come to Thorpe to - to work sort of thing. One or two families.
\par }}